Parliament did not support the amendment acquitting Tymoshenko
Ukraine's parliament today rejected a proposal to repeal the paragraph on the basis of which opposition leader Yuliya Tymoshenko was convicted as part of an amendment to the Criminal Code.
The amendment, which would have opened the way to the acquittal of the imprisoned former prime minister, was rejected by MPs during the second reading of the proposal to reduce sentences for economic offences.
Tymoshenko was sentenced in October to seven years in prison for concluding an allegedly disadvantageous contract with Russia to buy natural gas.
The verdict is not final, the court is to hear the convict's appeal in December.
Tymoshenko calls the verdict a political vendetta against the regime, and suspicions of bias in the court have also sparked the trial in the West.
The proposal to remove Article 365, on the basis of which the former prime minister was convicted, from the Criminal Code was supported by 147 MPs during the vote.
It needed 226 votes to pass.
