France and the rest of Europe have come under the radar of investors
A statistical whirlwind swept across Europe on Tuesday.
Individual states have published GDP data for 3Q.
The Czech economy stagnated quarter-on-quarter, Germany and France are growing.
But the bond market is now breaking records.
Investors are no longer looking only at Italy, but also at Spain, France, Austria and others.
The statistical offices of the euro area, Germany, the Czech Republic and some other European countries have published preliminary estimates of economic development for the third quarter.
Germany's GDP grew by an expected 0.5%, France by 0.4%.
At the same time, both countries revised data for the second quarter, in which Germany did better than expected (growth of 0.3% instead of 0.1%), while France reported that it appeared in a slight decline of 0.1% (the original data spoke of stagnation).
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent year-on-year in the third quarter of this year.
However, gross domestic product (GDP) stagnated quarter-on-quarter and, according to the CZSO, confirmed the trend of gradual slowdown in economic performance.
The results are worse than analysts' estimates.
Highlights
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent year-on-year in the third quarter of this year, but stagnated quarter-on-year.
The German economy grew by 0.5 percent in the third quarter, according to preliminary and seasonally adjusted data.
The economies of both the euro area and the European Union grew by 0.2 percent between July and September compared with the previous quarter, in line with analysts' expectations.
The Greek economy shrank by 5.2 percent year-on-year.
The yield on its 10-year bonds is at 28.45%.
Italian and Spanish bond yields are rising towards critical levels.
Austria, the Netherlands, France, Belgium, etc. are also starting to feel the problems...
Yields on Czech 10-year bonds remain below 4%, even though the situation in the region is deteriorating.
There are voices in Germany that the ECB should be the lender of last resort.
