Diet of an obese child: no breakfast and cold cuts for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with being overweight, with 9 percent of schoolchildren being overweight and 5 percent being obese.
Obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles, as the current survey showed.
Once again, it shows how important the environment in which a person grows up and the role models around him are for healthy human development.
For example, sausages appear on the tables of obese children up to half as often as in families of children of normal weight.
More than 19 percent of obese people had French fries for dinner the day before a survey linked to an educational event called Obesity is no coincidence.
It is also not customary in fat families to play sports, but this applies to most families of today's schoolchildren - only 15 percent of children answered that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and nearly 900 children from elementary schools from all over the Czech Republic took part in it.
It was the second year of the Obesity is no Coincidence event, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 schoolchildren from 4th to 8th grades have joined the project.
Proper eating and sufficient exercise in the family is one of the determining factors that causes a dramatically increasing number of overweight or even obese children.
"For example, only half of the respondents said that they eat five times a day in the breakfast-snack-lunch-snack-dinner regime, which is one of the basic prerequisites for proper nutrition," reads one of the survey results.
Without breakfast and sausage in the evening
Experts point out that relative details, such as regular family breakfast time, are also essential for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 percent of families of schoolchildren eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst thing was finding out that in a tenth of households there is no breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a proper daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that families of obese children are much more likely to consume unhealthy French fries.
Almost everyone – regardless of weight – drinks sugary sodas every day (70 percent).
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed regularly do sports, the result for their parents was less than half - 15 percent.
Build your own diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own menu according to their own taste and opinion.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition."
Among their favorite dishes there are a lot of floury, meat and sweet dishes.
"The great popularity of sweet sodas is particularly alarming," the survey final report states.
For lunch, pasta won over poultry as the main dish.
But the children practically did not want legumes at all, and the popularity of fish and midday vegetable dishes is also low.
Inclination to health
The survey also showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they are given the right information.
"In the control group of survey participants who filled in the questionnaire after the educational lecture Obesity is not a coincidence, there was in many cases a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy nutrition," the project results state.
This was noticeable, for example, in the case of sugary sodas, where more children would start to prefer ordinary water.
Children were also much more likely to tick poultry and fish as the main meal of the day in the questionnaire and would cut down on sweet foods and dumplings.
A stylist must also be a good psychologist, say the pros
In the introductory article about how stylists learn, I complained a bit that there was already a lot in the introductory lessons.
I had no idea what was going to happen next.
Lectures by three professionals in the field, dressing problematic characters and a seminar on how it works on set.
And it's going to get worse.
The closer we get to the final exam, the more information and practical tasks await us.
And even though the course takes place every Saturday and Sunday, it is really "packed".
This time, the headmistress Alenka and I discussed (there is not a single boy in the course) how to dress a woman who does not have a perfectly symmetrical figure.
And the vast majority of them are.
Someone has a short neck, someone has a boyish figure without proper curves and someone is overweight.
The stylist must know how to visually soften broad shoulders, lengthen the neck or add the necessary curves.
We got tips on how to emphasize the figure of a woman like Jennifer Lopez, i.e. bigger breasts and hips and a narrow waist, and at the same time not to dress a woman too provocatively.
For example, if the difference between the waist and hips is such that the skirt or trousers do not really fit, then it pays to have at least one such piece tailored.
You will definitely not regret it, because perfectly fitting clothes are priceless.
You will feel much better in a tailored skirt than in one that constantly shifts, rolls up, stands at the waist and so on.
A boyish figure, on the other hand, can afford to wear clothes with lashes, appliqués, embroidery or scoops.
Of course, there is a lot of such information and types of characters, so I'm glad I have a whole week to organize all the information in my head.
And I'm still afraid that given the homework assigned, it's too much.
Each of the students was assigned a celebrity to invent two outfits: day and evening.
We have to take into account the current appearance, fashion style of the personality and body type.
I will "dress" Miranda Kerr, you may know her from the Victoria's Secret campaigns.
In my mind, I rejoice, for me personally definitely better than Britney Spears, Christina Aguilera, who has recently gained about a hundred pounds (please take into account the exaggeration), or young Selena Gomez.
Clothes have to be cut from magazines or searched on the Internet and printed and then graphically processed.
Moodboard, as the whole result is called, then expresses our personal style and relationship to the graphic design.
Thinking about the graphic side of styling is important.
The stylist does not only dress physically, but also creates, for example, so-called product pages in magazines (for specific assignments, such as trendy handbags, coats, etc.).
Stylist and designer Mario Kameník told us about it.
But not until Sunday.
The stylist must have a general overview
Saturday's lecture full of information about the types of characters was enriched by three guests from the field.
Stylist Honza Pokorný, fashion designer Jakub Polanka and fashion photographer Ben Renč.
Jakub reminded us that fashion is an illusion and a stylist should be able to take advantage of it.
And a skilled stylist can work with one piece of clothing differently.
Variability is key in this case.
For example, such a trench coat (or if you want originally a trenchcoat) can be worn classically over jeans and a T-shirt as a coat, but you can also wear it on your bare body, put on pumps and take pictures as a dress.
Or just roll up the sleeves or collars and the whole look looks different.
"Play with it," he emphasized.
But what I appreciated the most was the following advice: "To work, you need to know the rules perfectly."
"Then you can start breaking them," James said.
Finally, it is clear to me why we crush all the precepts, what to combine with, for what, why, when even in fashion magazines we sometimes see something else.
Not to mention the shows.
Thanks to photographer Ben, I know that a stylist has to have many more variations of clothes ready than they can photograph.
So for a fashion story that will have ten pages (ten outfits), I have to be ready to "natajlovat" at least fifteen.
And also that in the photo clothes look and work in combination with other pieces sometimes completely different than in reality.
So we have to count on this when creating an outfit.
The fact that image and style sometimes make up to half of the success was confirmed to us by Honza Pokorný.
Just look at Madonna, who is not exactly a prodigy, but her image and marketing have made her a world star.
In the Czech Republic, the approach to using the services of stylists is rather cold.
Even familiar faces sometimes consider it unnecessary (it's enough that I know something, the way I look is secondary).
And if someone lets us create styling, then we should count on the fact that they will most likely dictate a completely different (smaller) size than it really has.
Then all we have to do is google and find out if the tabloids wrote about the fact that the celebrity had lost weight and so on.
Honza and Mario on Sunday told us that it is not enough for a stylist to orientate himself in fashion and be able to put together an outfit.
In her work, she primarily communicates with the people she dresses, so it is important to be a good psychologist.
To be able to judge people, not to pander to yourself, to stand by your opinion.
"When a manager orders you to sort through her wardrobe and add nice pieces, you can't throw out her whole wardrobe and say, oh my God, that's horrible."
"Find at least a few things to praise and recommend what they can be worn with," says Mario.
He also showed us specifically what the so-called "flat" or set bag must contain.
It's the one you fasten around your waist and have all the necessary props with you.
In addition to obvious things such as scissors, a hair roller or safety pins, there are also a silon thread (with which the stylist helps himself when photographing products such as handbags or hats), special clips that we use to fasten the back of the clothing if it is larger (a pin or other clamp is not allowed, it would damage the clothing), or a sewing.
In order not only to listen, but also to try something practically, we learned how to properly tape shoes.
Even when shooting in a studio where there is a flat surface, the sole could be damaged, let alone outside.
And so we glued and glued.
We must not even touch the shoes with scissors, so that they do not accidentally get damaged.
So you really need skill.
Mario pleased me when he praised my creation without reservation.
This skill is really not my friend.
This is just a tiny fraction of what we heard about the second weekend continuation of the course.
It is becoming more and more clear to me that styling on a professional level is really not a walk in the park, no matter who says what they want.
Need for Speed: The Run takes place across America.
Recension
The originally carefree ride turns into a routine morning shift due to a series of completely unnecessary sloppy mistakes.
Ambitions have largely been fulfilled, but it is of no use when no one seemed to want to do anything extra.
The new episode, subtitled The Run, raised high expectations before its release.
He promised to move the age-old racing series Need for Speed in a new direction and from the playable demos it seemed like a game that would not have to be in the genre of action racing only in numbers.
We were also curious to see how the inserted passages would turn out, in which the main character gets out of the car and runs on his own.
However, as usual with the NFS series, many things are a bit different than we expected.
These are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole is dragged down by a few unnecessary bugs that have appeared in the series more or less for several years.
So these are actually not even mistakes, but rather a manifestation of some incomprehensible laziness of the developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are introduced to a story whose main hero Jack has certain problems of a personal nature and as a solution offers participation in an illegal race across America.
You will get behind the wheel on the west coast in San Francisco and your task is to arrive first in New York.
The idea carries with it several interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then more than fifty races.
This means that each race takes place on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
One does not have the feeling for a moment that the game would offer the same thing all the time.
In addition, some of the environments are very nice to look at, although the technical level of graphics corresponds to previous parts of the series.
So it's nothing worldly.
But driving across deserts, autumn landscapes or high in snowy mountains is visually very pleasant.
In addition, the races are from time to time diversified by some atypical element.
In the desert, for example, you get caught up in a sandstorm that greatly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains you have to be careful not to be buried by an avalanche.
In addition, individual races are quite well planted in succession.
There are only a few types, but it is enough.
For a while, you try to overtake the required number of opponents (basically a classic race), then you catch up with time (a classic duel with a stopwatch) and then a duel with a single opponent awaits you.
From time to time, the police get involved in this, making your whole effort even more unpleasant.
A novelty is the passages outside the car.
It's more about interactive animations, where Jack usually runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right moments.
Nothing complicated.
Surprisingly, there are far fewer of these passages in the game than you would expect (specifically, perhaps even only three).
In the end, however, it is a good thing, because this element has no chance to become annoying and in the context of the above is one of the elements that diversify the game.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of the previous parts.
This means that nowadays it is definitely not who knows, but it can not be said that it would be a negative.
If you're looking for a realistic simulation, you'll have to look elsewhere.
But the more action-packed racing still suits the local driving model quite well, even though we could find a better one from the competition.
So far, so everything is in perfect order.
But problems begin to appear after some time.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not very good.
We do not expect a game of this type to calculate complex deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea how your car will behave before hitting any object, then probably not everything is quite right.
Typically, when tightly overtaking or passing cars in normal traffic, you sometimes only lightly lick each other, but other times, in an almost identical situation, your car ends up in wild pirouettes.
Or even attack.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn't really matter, but it will reliably tune you.
Restarts are handled in such a way that if you smash or go far off the track, the game throws you back to the last clue on the track.
But there are only five restarts available in each race.
When you run out of them, you have to start the race all over again.
It is therefore more of a tool in case something goes wrong than that you can explicitly rely on them.
Sometimes, however, even restarts do not help, they are solved only by the need to learn the part of the race by heart.
The big malady of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some corners need to be driven in a specific way, otherwise you simply will not fit into them.
Other times, you will meet "civilian" cars in the same configuration, whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
It sucks especially in situations where you see how between two oncoming cars the opponent in front of you easily passes, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to go around or brake them.
It does not matter when you reach them, because it is "calculated" so that the situation always occurs right under your nose.
Opponents have another advantage.
Throughout the game, you will come across several places where, again regardless of time, you will always be overtaken by the same opponent in the same place.
Most of all it hits at the end of the game on a long bridge, where you go in the opposite direction.
The opponent must get there in front of you, obviously, at any cost.
When it is driving in front of you, it makes it difficult for you to see the oncoming cars, so you will probably get a few times at first.
One can understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenaline-fueled, but the execution is so obvious that it will reliably quickly disgust you.
And it's a shame, because despite the simple driving model, the gameplay is fun and sometimes so action-packed that sometimes you literally can't keep track of where everything is flying.
And it basically does not matter whether it is due to the concept of fifty unique tracks, the ordering of races so that boredom has no chance, or anything else.
An unconventional idea is to exchange cars during races.
You have to watch out for gas stations by the roads, because that's where you can change the car, although in the vast majority of cases you can make do with what you have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, powerful American crashes for straight highways and exotic supercars for technical riding, such as on winding mountain roads.
The main story mode goes hand in hand with the challenge mode, which is a race in individual locations that you know from the story.
Here you earn not only medals, but also experience points for your profile, which is common to both challenges and story.
To get a higher driver level, various items are unlocked: starting with cars and ending with profile backgrounds.
It is also again connected to the online Autolog function, which, among other things, compares your achievements with other players and provides other community functions.
One of the other hard-to-understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car you get to the metro tunnel (so be it), where you drive in the dark on the rails (so be it).
Numbers between 150 and 200 km/h are flashing on the speedometer (so be it) and a metro train rushes in from behind and uncompromisingly scraps you.
In the editorial office, we will probably have a discussion for a few more days about whether no one really thought a little when creating the game, or whether the authors really consider us such big idiots.
The technical side of the game is nothing extra, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in a few cases even great.
It is annoying that in some of the more tense moments, the frame rate decreases, in some cases quite tragically.
However, this applies mainly to crashes with a larger number of participants, where smooth imaging would not be of any use to you anyway.
The sound is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to the widest possible range of rather younger audiences, a soundtrack from the category of "every dog a different village" was created, but it can be assumed that because of listening to music, the game will probably not be bought by anyone.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is thus quite embarrassing.
If the game avoided completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best NFS game in the last few years.
But this is how the game feels unfinished.
It's certainly fun, but be prepared for the mistakes to smash you in the eye with the power of airport headlights.
Charles University choirs will be heard at the concert Students of Velvet
The Festa Academica festival offers a combination of the celebrations of International Student Day and the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution with a musical experience for the third time.
Twenty high school and university choirs will perform during it.
The main focus of the festival are two concerts held on 17 November.
"Charles University has a large share in the festival."
"Among the participating choirs is the Choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanities, the festival committee will include Rector Václav Hampl," said Jakub Čaloun, head of the organizing team.
The highlight of the festival is a concert of high school choirs open to the public, which will take place on November 17 at 2 p.m. in the area in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program includes a composition by the prominent Czech jazzman Karel Růžička Celebration Jazz Mass.
In the evening, the concert "Velvet Students" will take place in the ceremonial premises of the National House of Vinohrady, featuring university choirs, including choirs of Charles University.
Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate the International Day of Students with dignity and commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present choral music to the public at the highest level and to develop creative cooperation between young people.
The main organizer is the Union of Czech Choirs in cooperation with the Johannes Kepler Grammar School.
The whole event was held under the auspices of the Mayor of the City of Prague, Bohuslav Svoboda, and the Rector of Charles University, Václav Hampl.
The festival will take place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
In addition to festive concerts, the schedule also offers a number of musical meetings, student happenings, matinees and other programs.
Detailed information can be found on the website of the festival www.festaacademica.cz
Ambassador to the EU Vicenová:
Czechs have a reputation as negativeists and Eurosceptics
"The Lisbon Treaty has quite significantly upset the balance between the institutions."
"I didn't expect it to be such a tough war."
"It will take five, six years for the situation to stabilize a bit, calm down and for all the players to get used to their new roles," Czech Ambassador to the European Union Milena Vicenová began her lecture at the Faculty of Law.
She showed how seriously she takes her motto "Comprehensibly and openly about Europe" already in the first part of the lecture, when she managed to describe the individual EU institutions and their relations in such a clear and comprehensible way that many lecturers from the Faculty of Law of Charles University could envy her.
Vicenova also praised the work of the new permanent President of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
"At first there was criticism that he was bland, that he was a grey official, that he could not fulfil any role, and I have to say that everyone was taken aback that he played the role excellently."
"He is a man who knows how to listen to twenty-seven member states, who communicates well with them and who has a clear vision of where the European Union should go."
She explained the new post of High Representative for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy in response to the question: "Who is the European Union? Which phone number should I call?", i.e. as an important step towards unifying and making EU policy vis-à-vis countries such as China or India more readable.
Nobody wants to ban us from cheese
Vicenová also addressed the agenda that the European Council has lived, is living and will live in the near future.
She described the Czech Presidency two years ago as a success.
The Czechs dealt with the emerging financial crisis, solved the gas crisis and organized a summit for the Eastern Partnership.
She described the fall of the government at that time as a major negative that damaged the Czech Republic very strongly.
The Czech representation in the EU is currently very busy.
In the words of the Ambassador, it was not only the Presidency that was "really busy", but also the subsequent financial crisis, which is still being dealt with today.
In addition, the Union's new seven-year budget still needs to be approved, which is becoming considerably more complicated due to the current economic situation.
Whether the budget will be lean and austere, which sectors will be given priority, which countries will be supported more and which less, is all on the agenda of future negotiations.
The Ambassador also recalled her main slogans, which she came to Brussels with: "About Europe clearly".
"I really don't like ugly abbreviations, foreign words, jargon that no one understands.
How is a citizen supposed to understand that in Brussels they really do not invent curved or round cucumbers, bananas of different sizes, or that someone really has to ban us cheese?"
He also wants to make better use of the EU environment and get more Czechs into European institutions.
A multi-speed Europe awaits us
According to the ambassador, Czechs have a reputation as Eurosceptics and people who notice the negative rather than the positive side of things.
In addition, she regrets the low representation of Czechs in European institutions.
According to her, many factors are to blame, such as the modesty of our candidates, their inability to write motivation letters, but also low support from the Czech side.
In addition to the successful Czech Presidency, she highlighted the strength and cooperation of the Visegrad Four.
"Believe me, when a Pole and a Hungarian come to me and a Slovak approaches, the Frenchman next to me says: 'Hey, what are you meeting there, what about your Visegrad Four?'
In the future, according to Vicen, the EU will mainly face new tough rules for the budgetary policies of member states.
He sees the concept of a two-speed, if not multi-speed, Europe, rather than a new "European federation" as very real.
"We have eurozone countries and non-eurozone countries."
"We have the Schengen area, we already have the institute of enhanced cooperation."
"For the first time, it was said that only the countries that want to cooperate and those that do not want to should stand by."
"There will be more institutes and it will be a strongly two-speed Europe," Vicenová expects.
In this regard, it also praised the role of the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in promoting the principle that all issues affecting the Union as a whole should be discussed among all Member States, not just between euro area countries.
Brand story:
Innovator IBM begins its second century of existence
If one were to search for a word that would most accurately describe IBM's strategy, the closest thing to it would probably be "long-term."
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution, it is a company perceived as very contemporary, and yet a hundred years have passed since its founding.
The foundation for this longevity was laid by the company's first CEO, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already coined the motto that many of the world's problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" thus became the imprint around which the life of the future giant would unfold (and also the name of an internal magazine that began to be published at IBM in 1935).
It was also the foundation of Watson's carefully constructed corporate culture.
"For us at IBM, long-term thinking means continuous movement towards the future.
IBM has survived and prospered for a century by staying true to its core values while not being afraid to change everything else.
This allowed us to transform technology, business and society during our first century.
We hope to achieve even more in the second hundred," said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current CEO, on the anniversary.
Sophisticated system
In the thirties, Watson approached the care of his employees similarly to the entrepreneur Baťa in the Czech Republic - people from IBM were among the first American employees to have paid vacation, insurance from their employer plus an elegant employee uniform and a sophisticated system for rewarding the best inventors and businessmen.
IBM's relationship with the customer has been equally sophisticated over the long term.
