Institutions with a good reputation
A strong position in the business is ensured by the company's strong internal and external image.
"From the beginning, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than just a technology company," Rosabeth Moss Kanter, a professor at Harvard Business School and author of a book on IBM, told the Economist.
"IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems using technology," said George Colony of Forrester Research.
As the company itself says, there is a difference between entering the market and thus creating the market.
IBM - or "Big Blue", as it is familiarly known in the United States because of its logo - has grown over a century into one of the largest companies in the world.
