Services account for the largest share of IBM's revenues, with software and hardware accounting for about a fifth.
In 1990, it was still the strongest representative of hardware with more than half of its share.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion worth of low-yielding assets, during which time it has invested $58 billion in promising technology purchases.
It has continued to invest since 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept the world for the first time.
IBM is following the legacy of its first CEO, Thomas J. Watson, who also increased investment during the Great Depression.
So far, IBM seems to be going through the current crisis untouched.
IBM's share price has skyrocketed by 120 percent since the beginning of 2008, and the company's net profit has been growing continuously.
IBM's corporate motto is to change everything but your values.
