IBM History: From Cheese Slicer to Space Flights
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a century ago, originally having the complicated name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM took over in 1924 - originally it was a brand used for the company's subsidiaries in Canada and South America.
The basis for the later IBM gave the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the eighties of the nineteenth century.
They owned technology such as the famous "attendance clocks," a clock that records an employee's arrival and going.
The architect of the new firm was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the firm's supervisory board until 1930.
Flint hired the head of a rival firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed IBM's founders - Watson's ideas are still built on an unbeatable corporate culture and identity.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began by manufacturing and selling all sorts of machines for business - from meat and cheese slicers to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson was in charge, sales doubled to nine million dollars and began a large-scale expansion to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that after nearly forty years in the boss's chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Jr.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence, developing the first programming language.
In the sixties, people and computers from IBM helped NASA control flights into space - to Mercury, Saturn and, in 1969, the famous flight of man to the Moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "PC" that set the computer standard of the time, called the IBM 5150, came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold the computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, on the contrary, bought the consulting part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and began to fully devote itself to consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that has paid off for IBM over the past three years is the Smarter Planet concept.
Its goal is the smart use of technology in previously unplanned areas and to improve the situation, for example, in transport or city administration.
For the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smarter Commerce" platform to help retailers manage the entire business cycle.
IBM also has a strong domestic history.
It established its branch in the former Czechoslovakia in 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM Czech Republic, it also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern Europe headquarters is based in Prague and there is also a world-class voice research team.
