How tour prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, travel agencies overwhelmingly sold only tours to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled on holiday to the sea in the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in the Crimea by the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and Hungary (Lake Balaton).
A bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime inclined to the West and the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia was subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely individually even within socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from that country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
At that time, travel agencies also offered tours to the West, but it was necessary to stand in line overnight with a sleeping bag or have "good friends" in the travel agency.
Even so, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange pledge, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not granted to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without a foreign exchange promise it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for the journey to the West.
By far, however, Czechs spent their holidays in the Czech Republic by far, which resulted in a large number of chalets and cottages that Czechs bought and this custom survives to this day.
Since 1989, travelling by Czechs has experienced a real revolution.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, which we no longer realize today, is that it was not possible to travel freely to Croatia, which is currently the most popular for us, until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right at the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the visa requirement to neighboring Western European countries was abolished, which started a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austrian Vienna or Germany.
For a long time, Czechoslovaks could not get enough of trips to the West, everyone wanted to go there at least for a while.
For example, in Paris, tours of Czechs slept in parks in tents, because our income at that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a guesthouse.
A typical feature of travelling Czechs at that time was to bring their own food, canned food, salami, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech crown, which finally allowed our tourists to freely buy Western currency after many decades.
However, our standard of living, and with it our average wages, were rising, which resulted in another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies began to regularly prepare charter air tours from 1997, which made air tours incredibly cheaper compared to the past thanks to the possibility of negotiating quantity discounts.
At the end of the 90s of the last century, Czechs already had visa-free travel to virtually all developed countries of the world, except the USA, which further facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution travel occurred in 2000, when the historically first direct charter flight to exotics was dispatched from the Czech Republic to Thailand due to considerable demand.
Since this year, direct charters have been flying with Czech tourists to warm distant countries every year, this winter there will be flights directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by around 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the USA cancelled visas for Czech tourists and thus our country definitively ranked among the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time in history, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history they spent more than 15 thousand on one foreign holiday, including the cost of the place of stay. CZK per person.
