The most beautiful pools in Europe
Jump into blue
Julia Stanek
A paddling pool from a Ufon point of view, a sumptuous pool in Budapest: Anyone travelling through Europe can experience its blue wonder - and after exploring the cities or travelling, let your tired legs rest in the thermal baths.
The book will show where wellness by the water is most beautiful.
When Iris Meder went on voyages of discovery over the past year and a half, it was not missing from her luggage: her swimsuit.
Lying on the water, she looked up at the artistically sculpted domes, swam opposite the marble putti (figures of a small naked boy, a child (with wings)) that awaited her at the edge of the pool, and admired the carefully restored Art Nouveau swimming pools.
If she liked a swimming pool, she immediately entered it in her notebook - with remarkable details about the construction method and the history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools have been explored in this way by the architectural historian Meder and are now presented in her just-published book "Badefreuden (The Joy of Bathing): People's Swimming Pools in Munich, Historic Swimming Pool Palaces in the Black Forest, "Hard Core Concrete Buildings" in Taunus.
Her "Journey to the Most Extraordinary Spas in Central Europe" led her through 13 countries: In addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited locations in Italy, France, Bohemia, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and one city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia each.
The 46-year-old German is a true enthusiast of swimming culture.
With sports, it is not too much, says Meder - only in the water it is something different.
It's infuriating that swimming fans have to settle for blue tiles and the smell of chlorine, while health runners can inhale the intoxicating scent of spruce forests or listen to the cheerful chirping of birds in the park.
"One day I asked why swimming pools always have to be so ugly," says Meder, a Vienna-based woman.
"So I started collecting nice swimming pools."
Water surface doubles architecture
Splashing in the diving pool and essential oils for the sauna - the well-being factor is therefore so great that it concerns all the senses, so much for Mrs. Meder.
And when the founders tried, swimming pools can be a real feast for the eyes: "Instead of a floor, one has a water surface in a spa."
"It's transparent, but it's also a reflection of the beauty of the building."
Everything is optically doubled: high vaults, colorful tiles, diving boards.
The small-format picture volume "Badefreuden (Badeuden) (Bathing Pleasures) " provides everything you need to know about the architectural and cultural history of historic oases of wellness on 190 pages - but above all it makes you want to jump into the blue.
The remarkable specimens were discovered by the collector of swimming pools Mrs. Meder during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent healing baths, such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Baths in Budapest, she found nitrate-containing water in the original karst cave (Miskolc-Tapolca Cave Baths) and thermal baths whose pools are filled with alkaline water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
On the other hand, many heated open-air swimming pools in Switzerland and Austria offer a wonderful spectacle. While you can see the whole city from Zurich's rooftop swimming pool, you can gaze at the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor pool of the spa in St. Anton – and: In the steam baths there is a window from which you can watch the hustle and bustle of the ski slopes.
Perhaps the most striking pool design awaits spa guests in Längenfeld: the Ötztal waterpark looks like a UFO that has just landed in the Alps.
Steam rises from three upwardly open basins in winter, while in the background of the Ötztal mountains it rises to the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool did the pool collector Mrs. Meder have the smell of chlorine rising to her nostrils.
Many thermal baths smell of sulphur, and the Árpád spa in Békescsaba, Hungary, smells of fuel oil to such an extent that one can hardly believe that one has reached the healing baths.
The smell comes from the alkaline bicarbonate healing water, which is almost black and whose deposits stick to the skin as soon as one slips into the pool - a rather strange wellness experience.
However, there was also one place that Iris Meder was disappointed in her search for a nice spa: When she wanted to visit the Czech solar and climatic spa Luhačovice, she came across a closed terrain.
In 1902, the spa designed by architect Dušan Jurkovič was closed in the meantime.
When Mrs. Meder looked through the crumbling windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds growing massively between the tiles.
On the other hand, they stood up to extinction in a charming swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
This spa has already completed three phases of construction; One can discover not only neo-Romanesque elements that date back to its creation in 1844, but also the Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, which was added around 1900.
Since careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been a favourite spa spot for pool connoisseur Iris Meder, and not just because she comes from the Black Forest.
"It is already a feat to combine such diverse architectural styles into such a beautiful complex," says Meder.
For such a palace, immersion in a thermal pool is probably a marginal matter.
