21st Century House in Vienna
Moved pavilion
Ingeborg Wiensowski
A story of architecture with highs, lows and happy endings: The Austrian pavilion from the World Exhibition in Brussels in 1958 won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, remained empty and desolate.
Now it is reopened as a showhouse.
When one is passionate about modern post-war architecture, bright forms, glass halls, bold booms and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion by architect Karl Schwanzer is an apt and famous example for the Brussels World's Fair of 1958.
The Schwanzer Pavilion received the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its light and lofty steel and glass structure.
The building is still considered a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so famous that he also built a pavilion in Austria for the next world exhibition.
With his legendary four-cylinder BMW Palace plus the key construction in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
Its pavilion, designed as a temporary exhibition building, was placed in the Schweizer Garten near Vienna's Südbahnhof (South Railway Station) after the World's Fair, reconstructed and opened the Museum of the 20th Century in 1962 - it was named the "House of the 20th Century".
However, the building was not suitable for the museum, neither spatially nor technically - there were no walls for hanging art exhibits, no suitable climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art had a new stand in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building was empty and fell into disrepair more and more.
Now architect Adolf Krischanitz has reconstructed the pavilion, it is now called the "House of the 21st Century" and will be used in the future as a Museum of Contemporary Art.
On Tuesday evening, the Museum Belvedere, to which the palace belongs, will open its first exhibition there - a happy intention in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Belvedere Gallery in 2007, made a new beginning.
Husslein-Arco, a graduate art historian with a distinguished career, including figure skater in her youth, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Salzburg Museum of Modernism, pushed through vigorous reconstruction among politicians and conservationists, procured public funds and private sponsorship money, and determined the use.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of sculptor Fritz Wotruba should be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, a café and a bookstore should be built, and an office building would have to be built.
Strict supervision, low budget.
Krischanitz was the ideal cast for the performance.
Not only did he sensitively reconstruct and expand Joseph Olbrich's Art Nouveau buildings in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied with Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was an "extremely important place" for him, where he viewed exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original design and also knew the problems of the building, which had already lost its generosity and lightness when it was relocated to Vienna and reused.
There were much bigger problems with the current renovation: The building was a "catapult for energy", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass façade were replaced, fiberglass reinforced insulating glass was used, and the glass roof was replaced with special safety glass.
Cold bridges-steel beams were reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings rehabilitated.
Two underground floors provided space for new use, a recessed lighting channel between the building and the street provides lighting, and a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still lofty Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original entrance door has been preserved, the building is painted in an old anti-corrosion red-brown color tone.
And the cinema is even exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under the strict supervision of the heritage office and a low budget.
"Often a material had to be found that was good and cheap, and the heritage office also liked it," says Krischanitz, pointing to the broken basement floor.
Despite all the pressures, problems and renovations, the building remained flexible and airy.
It was difficult with the pavilion, "which came here from Brussels," Krischanitz, a typical "Drop-in-the-City-history," said recently.
Such architecture, he said, is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "inspire proper self-confidence."
In this case, however, the 21st Century House is not in an inappropriate place, as an urban happy coincidence has happened: A completely redesigned "City Quarter near the Main Station" with office and residential buildings is being built around the Schweizer Garten.
And perhaps another lucky coincidence will happen: the 21st Century House could receive support from another Krischanitz building, as collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the Berliner Temporäre Kunsthalle and, as can be heard, is already negotiating with the city for a neighborhood at the Schweizer Garten site.
