UBS knows what the customer is looking for: safety.
But the Swiss bank's idea, UBS and Credit Suisse, has sometimes been suppressed or betrayed, as the head of a small Swiss private bank discovers.
He would rather not read his name in the newspapers, and in the end, like all Swiss bankers, he also does business with the two big banks.
UBS may have grown too bigger, he finds, especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons have spread.
The Swiss probably have nothing more to say.
"And if they did, they had long since adapted to Anglo-Saxon ways."
Indeed, it was Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed UBS, causing it first high profits and then disaster: No European financial institution has lost as much money in the jungle around Subprime as Schweizer Großbank.
On October 15, 2008, the disaster was obvious.
"On that Wednesday, the governing coalition of a small country of seven million decided on the largest rescue operation in the history of its nation," writes author Lukas Hässig in his book "Der UBS-Crash".
Up to 68 billion francs, or about 45 billion euros, were approved by politicians to save a standing big bank from bankruptcy.
How could this happen?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem primarily in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three Swiss big banks merged into a massive concern.
A bank was created, which at the merger was already too big for a small Switzerland - and continued to grow.
It helped that UBS's two different banking predecessors were complementary: one rich but sleepy bank in Zurich with a focus on asset management, and poorer but more internationally involved.
Suddenly, internationalized investment bankers came profitably to a lot of money with which they could spin a big roulette.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, head of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then chairman of the board.
"I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were the team of the future," says banking expert Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the highly intelligent, modest one who knows a lot about models and statistics, and Ospel, the stomach-driven man who has worked his way up from banking science."
But Ospel is said to have relied on Wuffli towards the end.
And Wuffli probably made a decisive mistake in the end: "He probably thought his models were reality," says Geiger.
"This is a tragic case."
Tragic, perhaps.
The plain is: Pride preceded the fall.
UBS employees clearly remember the executive meetings at which Group CEO Wuffli repeated the same slogan over and over again: Knock Goldman Sachs down.
The American bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
It listed "League Tables," a waiting list that documented the success of banks at the time.
In it, UBS tried to place at the very top.
She has already taken a few steps.
In the foreign exchange and stock trade, she participated in the game at the very top.
But the corporate consultants in charge highlight one weakness: In international interest trading, in bankers' "Fixed Income" language, there may be a big gap behind the largest banks.
UBS may have gaps in U.S. mortgage products.
To close this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that nearly cost it its existence.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and the risk-hedging fund it set up invested in Subprime's US investments.
It developed into a massive machine that repackaged securities into US mortgage loans and passed them on - while also retaining the risks themselves.
Also when other banks were looking for a way out for a long time.
"Back in the summer of 2007, when the housing market was in flames, UBS was still buying there," says Geiger, a banking expert.
How great is the euphoria, so deep the fall.
Manager after manager had to leave when attempts to clean up became more difficult than thought.
The positions at UBS became the ejection seat and are still swinging today.
Whoever runs a big bank now has an almost unmanageable job.
They need to find a strategy for the bank, where all close business models have disappeared.
Geiger, a banking expert, already has an idea: End investment banking, concentrate on asset management, return to Swiss roots.
The bank doesn't (yet) want to go that far.
But investment banking is about to decline significantly, that much is now clear.
Next Thursday, the bank's new boss, Sergio Ermotti, wants to present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Swiss Italian was seen as a temporary solution when the bank surprisingly parted ways with its predecessor, Grübel.
Meanwhile, he has asserted himself: He is to run UBS business for a long time, the Zurich bank said on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants to bring the investment bank back to its mid-nineties.
3500 posts will be deleted.
But that won't be enough.
UBS needs a vision.
Who is it?
What does he want to make money with?
These are the questions that Axel Weber is already asking.
Publicly, however, he says only that he and his wife will first find an apartment in Zurich.
Next year.
