Smart crows are spreading in cities
In many places, ravens are considered "problem birds": But these highly intelligent animals can no longer be expelled from cities, experts say.
Some like them, others would like to get rid of them quite quickly: Crows have been part of the city's image for centuries, yet in some villages complaints about dirt and noise caused by animals accumulate.
At the same time, there is no remedy in sight against the "problem birds".
Ravens can no longer be expelled from cities, experts said at the first crow symposium in Leer, East Frissia.
There, experts from all over the federal territory consulted on possible solutions.
They are looking for alternatives in cities
Conservationists also derived the city's problems from the exodus of specially protected ravens: The use of chemicals in agriculture is likely to be increasingly destroying traditional areas for living.
Persecution, growing development and felling of typical nesting trees make life difficult for birds.
Crows are protected.
Large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs are in Soest in Westphalia, in the northwest, including Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen and Leer.
There, a 2005 controversial project to mass-kill crows in a rural district sparked negative headlines.
Critics have called the trapping of animals in bird traps and beating them with sticks particularly brutal.
"Normal expulsion, scaring, brings nothing", as the urban planner and landscape painter Werner Klöver from Leer discovered.
Removing nests by spraying water or cutting down trees often has undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
"Animals retreat, large colonies split and divide into other places."
Scaring is conceivable only as an exception in hospitals, retirement homes or schools.
"We have to live with them, we won't get them out."
Without the surrounding area, the problem of cities cannot be solved, was the opinion of Mayor Wolfgang Kellner of Leer.
A combination of driving animals out of sensitive residential areas and enticing them to settle elsewhere is conceivable.
"Information boards instead of chainsaws," on the other hand, psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens promoted because of the completely different treatment of animals: "One bump in the face is ultimately the best way to endure self-confidence."
Mrs. Jürgens co-founded the Ascherberg Crow Trail in Schleswig-Holstein, where information boards provide information about the life of the highly intelligent raven.
In the meantime, the project is said to have already been accepted by tourists.
Jürgens also had her own opinion on the criticism of the noise caused by birds: "Every volume of communication is at stake here, they have a lot to say to each other."
The intelligence and skill of animals are legendary: Ravens don't just use tools to get a treat, they even make their tool as an aid.
Researchers from the University of Cambridge recently tested the behavior of four ravens to see how far the birds' intelligence reaches.
In one experiment, birds quickly learned that they had to bring stones to the collapse of a structure to reach a moth larva.
Without much training, they knew what size and shape a stone had to be to cause the platform to collapse.
In the second attempt, the cunning crows then had to solve a more difficult problem.
In a vertically built cylinder, the researchers placed a tiny container with a moth larva.
With their beaks, birds could not reach their prey.
But the researchers put pieces of wire there.
From these, all four animals shaped a hook, with the help of which they fished the container from the pipe by the handle.
Three of the four field ravens even managed to get stuck.
