Massacre on a personal level
Peter Englund's emotionally powerful new book, The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, begins with such a long list of characters that it makes your head spin.
One piece of advice on what to do at that point: Carefully tear out this page and bookmark it.
You will become very familiar with all the people in Mr. Englund's novel narration, and this list will serve as a navigation - a kind of beacon - when, like the men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book we are discussing here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite aptly, as an "anti-historical work".
It contains several well-known names, important treaties or famous battles, while it is almost devoid of ambassadors, energetic journalists and debates on tactics and equipment.
It's not so much a book about what happened, the author explains, as "a book about what it was like." It deals mainly with "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and Sorrow" combines the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from female students and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go mad or die.
Their lives flicker, like candle flames lit in a church, new ones added to the tangle of fates, while others fade away.
Mr. Englund's book is different from classic historical novels.
It modifies the idea that World War I was all about horrific trench warfare on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
In this book, the soldiers deal with problems with bee nests falling on them, having to spend Christmas in the shadow of pyramids, or struggling with the presence of tsetse flies.
Almost from the beginning, it is a very moving read.
War will consume people's lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina reeking of gunpowder.
When cannon fire starts in the distance and you are a woman who is at home with her children, do you run away or stay?
Who is actually coming?
Almost no one understands what is happening, not even why the whole war was started.
"The vacuum created by the lack of facts," Mr. Englund observed, "has been filled with conjecture, conjecture, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors."
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are mostly taken from biographies, letters and other materials already published.
The descriptions of their lives may sound scary and engaging, but the inclusion of small moments and details makes them completely vivid and believable.
Many of them deal with hardship and coping with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says: "Substitutes, substitutes everywhere."
