Walls Have Eyes: How Scientists Are Researching You on Facebook
Before Anders Behring Breivik became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, he was just another young man to present his anti-immigrant views online.
On Monday, Braivik, who confessed to a July killing spree that left 77 people dead in Norway, attended his first public court hearing.
Although Breivik could have acted alone, he was by no means alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time at the computer during the preparation of the attack, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting right-wing groups on social media sites.
After this summer's tragedy, scientists want to learn more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just hit Facebook.
"We realised that getting them wasn't that hard at all," says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent British research team's report on European digital populism.
Facebook's stock of personal information is so extensive, Bartlett says, that researchers simply used advertising on the site to pinpoint the demographic they were looking for — something marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe, then focused attention on them and sent them advertisements. However, instead of inviting them to join a new group or offering them diet products, they were asked to fill out a questionnaire asking questions about their level of education, their attitude towards violence, and their optimism about their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries – without ever having to leave the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research," Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not all that surprising: the online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young men who are irritated by rising levels of immigration.
But on the other hand, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, democratic, and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind a computer screen."
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists, and policy researchers use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends hidden behind status updates, posts on walls, and pressed "Like" buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. On average, each of them provides three different pieces of data per day, making the social network an "information supernova" that is behind the development of many new research. The number of academic papers with the word Facebook in their titles has risen to almost 800% compared to five years ago.
For some researchers, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the ability to study people without having to bother them on the street.
"It used to be that if you wanted to do a survey of people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to get to the side, but they'd never let you in," Bartlett says.
"Facebook is taking all of that away — you just go straight to them."
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid socio-health problems.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, a research team found that college students who discussed their drunken performances on Facebook were much more at risk for the problem of alcoholism than students who kept silent on the topic.
Moreno suggests that students' peers monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who posts too many drunken statuses.
"You can't solve the problem if you can't diagnose it," Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior, and Development at the Seattle Children's Research Institute, told the Washington Post.
"We found a way to identify children at risk that we otherwise wouldn't have a chance to discover."
Facebook itself is constantly probing the data of its users.
The site's information team has compiled statistics on the connection between relationship statuses and St. John's Day. Valentine's Day, voter turnout in 2010, and the nation's satisfaction coefficient (mainly using the information they had access to - advocates of Internet freedom have long argued that the site should make its information treasure available for research to others).
But Facebook users know that the site follows them whether they like it or not — in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site needs to provide their personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don't even know about?
Scientists have clear rules on how to collect data offline. However, online data is accessible to everyone.
"I don't think most users even thought that scientists could look at their profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, of a 2006 study he conducted using his students' public Facebook walls.
