7 Lessons from the Lost Steve Jobs Interview in Movie Coming to Theaters This Week
As soon as Steve Jobs died on October 5, the opinions of people began to emerge who compared him to Henry Ford - and voted him the greatest modern inventor for his genius.
What will be true about Jobs' recently rediscovered interview, which was dusted off for a special coming to theaters this week, for Apple fans, is that his creative mind had a perfect understanding of the business processes and workflows behind his products.
He was an amazing designer, a dreamer, and a self-proclaimed member of the hippie movement, but also a pedantic organizer and a man who fine-tuned every little detail – he believed that many entrepreneurs suffer from "the idea that 90 percent of their work is a really great idea... [But] between a great idea and a great final product, there is still a long way to go."
In 1995, Bob Cringely worked on the TV show The Triumph of Computer Fools, about the dawn of personal computers. During the filming, a unique, more than hour-long interview took place.
By then, it had been a decade since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was busy with his new computer company, NeXT, anxiously awaiting the general public's adoption of the Internet.
In the end, only a short portion of Cringely's entire interview was used in the TV show, and the original copies of the interview were said to have been lost in transit.
Shortly after Jobs' death, however, VHS copies were found in the director's garage.
It is this material, slightly edited, that forms the basis of the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which is heading to select theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who is notorious for his reluctance to give longer interviews, Jobs seems surprisingly excited to talk about his technology philosophy and business strategies.
And he also proves to be a very thoughtful person.
Four times during the interview, there is a longer pause between the question and the answer - 10 to 15 seconds of thinking, when you can see how Jobs thinks through the answer perfectly to make it as concise and accurate as possible.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, when he seems impatient with Cringely's questions and drives him to get to more important issues and topics faster.
The interview was filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod, and iPhone, and features frighteningly prophetic thoughts as Jobs assesses what other companies are doing right and wrong, while offering his own vision of the future in the field of computing.
It's one thing to read posthumous evaluations of Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about Jobs, whom we see here as an eager dreamer in the heyday of his genius.
He has his own vision of what things could and should look like.
It wasn't long before he had put his ideas into practice.
A quick summary of seven scenes from The Lost Interview that are definitely worth noting:
How he learned to run a business:
"In my years in business, I've always asked, 'Why are you doing this? and the answer was always the same: Well, that's just how it's done."
No one knows why they do what they do, they never think deeply about business-related things.
That's what I found out.
Jobs goes on to describe his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
He was completely confused by the way costs were recorded - they often began with the inscription "standard costs", the amount of which he could only guess. At that point, he decided to go his own way - he developed an automatic tool that guaranteed that they could determine trading costs in no time.
How he performed a mischief on the Pope:
Jobs recalls the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed people to effectively hack into a telephone company and make free calls anywhere in the world.
Much has been written about the device in the past, but Jobs' enthusiasm for describing the Blue Box as a tool of power is contagious.
He tells how he and Wozniak tested the device using a pay phone, and during the call they were transferred from one AT&T network to another, while using as many satellites as possible.
"We've weaved around the world at least half a dozen times, so when we shouted something into a paid phone, it came from the other phone at the door a minute later," Jobs laughs.
"We were young and we found that we could build something on our own that could drive billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world."
The two of us made a little thing that could control a much bigger giant – it was an incredible experience and I don't think Apple would have been created without it.
Jobs goes on to describe the prank he and Wozniak almost pulled to the end. They called the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asked if they could speak to the Pope, posing as Henry Kissinger as best they could.
Gradually, increasingly senior members of the Catholic Church were called in to speak with an American diplomat in the middle of the night, and just before they woke the Pope himself to the phone, the pair chuckled and hung up the receiver.
How he fell in love with technology (and was on the phone with Bill Hewlett):
When he was 12 and looking for spare parts to build a frequency meter, he looked up Bill Hewlett's number in the phone book and called him.
Not long after their 20-minute conversation, Jobs had already secured a summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"She influenced me unbelievably. It was the only company I knew at the time, and it shaped my view of what a company is and how it should treat its employees."
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made."
It was as big as a suitcase, had a CRT monitor, and I immediately fell in love with it.
As a teenager, I went higher and higher at HP, hanging around that computer and starting to write programs for it.
How they invent innovations:
In several places, Jobs talks during the interview about inventing new products on the fly.
Early in his career, when he went to sell a few printed circuit boards, a customer asked him to put together an entire computer for him.
He had only 30 paid days, during which he had to invent, assemble and deliver the finished equipment.
When he was later at Apple, he recalls the challenges they faced developing a computer mouse:
"I remember arguing quite wildly... They yelled at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300], until I got tired of it, and I went out and found a designer."
Ninety days later, we were able to make a perfectly reliable mouse for $15.
How big companies are running out of breath:
Long before he led Apple's resurrection, Jobs wisely predicted that many industry leaders would waver in their vision and lose market share.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers or printers, so what's next?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company can no longer be more successful.
At that point, sales and marketing dominate, so companies are headed by people who are in charge of this, while people in charge of their own products are excluded from the decision-making process.
The technological genius that has led the company to its unshakable position is now being replaced by people who have no idea of good or bad products - skill and technical knowledge are essential.
That's exactly what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned literally the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times bigger than it is, it could have been the Microsoft of the nineties...
Instead of winning, however, they made a loss.
How he takes innovation as an art form:
"There is still a long way to go and a lot of work between a great idea and a great final product... And as that great idea evolves, it changes and grows."
During that time, you will learn a lot about him.
You have to make a number of compromises - certain things you just can't force electrons, glass, robots or factories to do.
You have to keep 5,000 things in mind all the time - different concepts - and put them together...
At the end of the day, it depends on taste—you try to think of the best things humanity has ever created, and in a way you try to project them into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, but the best artists steal.
I've never been ashamed of stealing the best ideas.
The Macintosh company was so amazing and successful because the people who worked there were excellent musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, and coincidentally the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren't for computers and new technology, they would be able to do amazing things in completely different industries.
