How to recognize a lie
A cursory glance at recent headlines tells us how serious and pervasive lies and deceptions are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy alleging that he sexually harassed several women — both sides say the other is lying.
Penn State administrators were charged with perjury when they tried to hide records of a retired football coach sexually assaulting a boy.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught with his microphone down telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie has destroyed entire careers and shaken the stability of many countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by publishing information that was immediately refuted by indisputable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of using campaign funds to try to conceal his extramarital affair.
And no one will ever forget the media circus that revolved around Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term in office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Stories of cheating at school and university abound.
There are cases where teachers themselves give their students test answers, just to make them look good in their testimonials.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending the message that lies and deception are acceptable.
How many scams do we encounter?
Studies show that you lie somewhere between 10 and 200 cases in a single day.
Suppose many of them are merciful lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first ten minutes of their first meeting.
Identifying lies, or "recognizing lies," is an essential skill that everyone should learn, whether for personal or professional reasons.
But it's not a parlor game that's like, say, a Charade where you shout, "I've got you." Deception recognition is a serious branch of science working with scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities in the course of detailed research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and philosophy.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lies have been debunked.
Liars calmly look you in the eye.
It's not like they're stuttering, stuttering, blushing, or fidgeting.
But don't assume that liars are difficult to spot and expose.
A trained lie identifier can reveal the truth from sentence structure, small facial expressions, the way questions are created and their timing.
Having spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from the vast and evolving lie recognition industry, it is clear that deception detection is a modern skill that is easy to learn and can be of great help in today's complex world – especially if your job responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or leading people.
Good liars are good at reading others, letting their guard down, directing their emotions, and intuitively realizing how the other party accepts them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies, while women tell more "aimed at others" lies—mostly to protect someone's feelings—that married people lie to their partners less often than single people (though the lies they tell are usually "outrageous").
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of the subject.
This is called "initial observation."
Thanks to him, later findings will have something to compare with.
Note the posture of the subject, his laughter, work with the voice.
You should know if someone routinely taps their feet all the time so you don't wrongfully accuse them of lying just because they start tapping their foot in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to identify clusters of false verbal and nonverbal behavior.
But take this only as a warning sign, not as proof of a lie.
People telling a lie may stop moving their upper body when trying to remember their made-up story, they may turn the toes of their shoes to the door, lean toward the exit, significantly change their posture, or show "relief after the conversation" — exaggerated relief and change position when the difficult confession is behind them.
Interviewers often give a false signal that the interview is over, just to see what the relief will look like when it's over.
Also perceive the subject's language.
There is a famous story about how Scott Peterson once misspoke and used the past tense to claim that his murdered wife was alive, which sparked a nationwide search for her body.
Deceiving individuals may also express themselves in a measured manner: "I had no sexual relationship with this lady... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat the difficult question in its entirety.
The most common verbal signs are very subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "palliative language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... from what I know... to the best of my knowledge."
We don't get much of a factual in such an answer, and it's often another warning sign.
There is no magic to detect every lie, but it is possible to acquire the skills to spy on a lie.
With the help of these skills, a person will have a better chance of not falling for a liar and cheater in his personal and professional way.
