Patti LaBelle is accused of making a toddler vomit in fear
A New York family claims that singer Patti LaBelle stormed the lobby of their Manhattan home and scared their daughter into vomiting.
The singer's performance on "Lady Marmalade" scared eighteen-month-old Genevieve Monk so much that she suffered "personality changes, sleep disturbances" and "heightened fear of strangers," her family said in a lawsuit filed in the Manhattan Supreme Court.
On November 10 of last year, stage technician Kevin Monk, his wife Roseanna, a kindergarten teacher, and Genevieve were preparing for a family trip.
When Kevin Monk pulled up the car, Roseanna Monk went down with her luggage to the lobby of their Riverside Boulevard house, carrying Genevieve with her.
Roseanna Monk said she paused at the door for a moment and put the baby down for a moment.
"Someone showed up behind me and said, 'Do you know what your daughter is doing?'" I said 'yes' and left to pick her up."
LaBelle reprimanded the pregnant woman irritably.
"In an aggressive tone, she told me, 'You shouldn't put your daughter by the door,'" Roseanna Monk said.
"I told her, 'I'm not interested in your opinion.'"
She became enraged and began to speak vulgarly - shouting loudly the most vulgar expressions...
She had a bottle of water with her and started splashing water from it.
She claims that Genevieve had a hysterical fit.
"I said to the woman, 'Look what you did to my daughter,'" the child's mother said.
LaBelle threw herself at her mother — who still had Genevieve in her arms — and was only stopped by her escort, who then dragged her into a waiting car, Roseanna Monk testified.
Meanwhile, the daughter was screaming so hard she vomited, she added.
Later, the family sent a letter demanding an apology from LaBelle, but received no response.
LaBelle's lawyer and spokesperson have not responded to our calls to comment on the case.
The lawsuit is seeking unspecified damages, but the family's attorney, Sam Davis, said he took up the case free of charge and that the family plans to donate all of the money to a charity dedicated to children with cancer.
"The purpose is to force Patti LaBelle to take responsibility for her actions," Davis said.
"Such behaviour is totally unacceptable, especially when directed against a school teacher holding an eighteen-month-old child."
Climate Toughness Slows Down the Economy
During the first year of Mario López Valdez's government, unemployment and unreliability rose in Sinaloa, foreign investment declined, and with it the economy
The year 2011 will go down in Sinaloa's economic history. This is the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, which calls itself the government of change. This government has brought with it great expectations in terms of economic progress, however, due to adverse weather conditions at the beginning of the year, no growth has been recorded and there has even been a decline in the main indicators of economic development.
Low February temperatures caused millions of losses in agriculture, limited the growth opportunities of the state economy, are responsible for a decrease in economic activity by 3.6% in the first semester of this year. Agriculture experienced a historic decline of 31.16%, disrupting the momentum of other economic sectors as well.
According to the damage report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, damage was recorded on 582,835 hectares of cultivated land, of which 78.03% was completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07% was found to be partially damaged. The main destroyed crops include vegetables, corn and peas.
The decline in economic activity until November caused a constant increase in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the state's unemployment rate has seen an increased increase during the first three quarters. From January to March, 55,053 residents of the state of Sinaloa were unemployed, representing an unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment increased to 5.28%, and between July and August the average unemployment continued to rise, reaching 6.19%, representing approximately 74,000 unemployed. Compared to the first quarter, the number of unemployed increased by 18,969 persons.
Less liquidity
Unemployment during the year in the state of Sinaloa is due to several factors. According to Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the UAS Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on the steps that have been taken at the public policy level.
"We are seeing rising unemployment, which is related to various factors. These include, but are not limited to, the loss of liquidity in the market due to resource constraints due to legislation passed by Congress in the context of the fight against money laundering. It's not easy for people who illegally take possession of dollars, to earn them, to invest them or to use them for something," he said.
Stop migration
López Cervantes said that the demographic factor is also contributing to the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people going abroad to work, to the United States, has decreased, both because of the difficulty of entry and because even if these people get abroad, it is difficult for them to find work. So people stay and demand work from our state, and so unemployment is rising," he said.
Unreliability
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is also deteriorating due to the growing unreliability that prevails in the area of working conditions. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of the state's employed population works without paying benefits to the Social Security Administration.
Unemployment and unreliability are compounded by other features of the labour market, such as low wages. This administrative area has the lowest salaries in the country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of workers in the state of Sinaloa was 5,352 pesetas through September, well below the national average of 7,375 pesetas.
Shortening foreign direct investment
Along with the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, 2011 also saw the most significant decline in foreign direct investment in the last 10 years. According to the Ministry of Finance, in the January-June period, foreign direct investment amounted to $630,697, a decrease of 87.74% from the amount of $5,143,312 for the same period in the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the state government reports investments of 17, 280 million pesetas per year. These investments were mainly directed to service businesses.
Debt
In the context of a downturn scenario, the state's government asked the state Congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos. This would be used to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas to boost the economy. The local congress approved a loan of 2,600 million pesos. Until November, no gains on debt were recorded in any sector of the state economy.
Reaction
According to business sector representatives, the first year of Mario López Valdés' government highlighted the government's lack of management skills.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Transformation Industries, said that in 2011 there was a lack of alignment of the will of individual sectors, including the state government itself.
"Economic development in Sinaloa has been really small this year. We must work intensively to regain the land we lost this year. We have to redouble our efforts in 2012, there has been a lack of harmonisation of all our efforts and, in particular, of the correct and synchronised functioning of this new government. Hopefully next year will be much better," he said.
The slowness of the economy
Loredo López said events such as the frost at the beginning of the year brought the state's economy to a standstill and limited its development and growth.
"The weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including frosts. One of the main consequences was the slowdown of the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to restore the dynamism that would have allowed an acceptable level of movement of processes, products and services to be achieved. Therefore, at the end of the year, we were well below the expected forecasts," he said.
Redefining the mission
According to Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Employers' Confederation of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, it is necessary to push the state towards more dynamic productive activities.
"Generally speaking, we see that work is being done. We believe that it is necessary to prepare a long-term plan in which the goals and economic direction of the state would be redefined, because it is important to mobilize all the material and human resource potential that Sinaloa has," he said.
The work ahead of us
Chairman Coparmex stressed the importance of setting out a vision for the future that better guides the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in various areas, there have been some advances in the area of economic development, but it is important to create a long-term plan," he said.
He said the current administration has shown progress in terms of public policy leadership.
"There are elements that make it possible to say that the government is trying to be welcoming. I can say that there is a lot of work to be done and I think the government is aware that there is also a lot of work ahead of us," he said.
