He said that last year, under the administration of Jesús Aguilar Padillo, the state failed to fulfill the relevant supplies, and therefore at the beginning of the new period the city had to apply for a loan to pay more than 7 million that the state administration did not give them.
"The same thing happened to us in the previous six-year period, because the state did not have the economic capacity to participate and the programs went on. In order to get to these programs this year, we had to raise funds to cover what the state had not completed," he explained.
Despite the fact that there is a promise from state officials regarding the transfer of these resources, he said that a request has been sent to Armand Villarreal, Secretary for Administration and Finance, to expedite the proceedings and the corresponding percentages arrived as soon as possible.
"They were supposed to give us 12 million, and although the year is coming to an end, we haven't even received a peso yet."
Court approves 'end of analogue broadcasting' in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals with digital ones is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme State Court (SCJN) has dismissed a constitutional lawsuit brought by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against a presidential decree that seeks to speed up the so-called "shutdown of analogous signals" and implement it in 2015 instead of 2021. He stated that the necessary eight votes had not been found to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the court, Juan Silva Mezo, believed that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his powers when he issued a decree listing the steps that will lead to the transition to terrestrial digital television.
With this result, the action brought by the Senate was dismissed because the qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree in question was dismissed, and it remains in force.
The draft judgment drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero proposes the possibility of declaring the decree unconstitutional, since the regulation of all issues relating to radio and television is a matter reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel). This violates the principles of hierarchical subordination and the exception of the law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cødero herself voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies supported the constitutional dispute in an effort to fight the decree. Minister Sánchez Cordero accepted the demands and suspended the application of the decree and all actions described therein to lead to the digital transition.
The ministerial meeting also decided to dismiss the lawsuit filed by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the discussion on the proposal, which is also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the arguments of the proposal to the effect that the federal executive could not structure measures through general norms to prepare the public administration.
"I don't think that even if it did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulator," noting that planning public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate to determine the direction of the state.
The replacement of analogous signals with digital signals is one of the biggest changes the world has experienced in recent years. It is related to better use of the radioelectric spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
It believes that delaying change would mean delaying the benefits of digitalisation, which requires decisions of public interest. Digitization has not only a technical dimension, but "also touches on economic, social, political and national security issues".
As he emphasized, these issues "require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of the economic direction of the state. It encompasses a whole series of powers which the Constitution confers in the hands of the government of the State."
He recalled that a number of countries around the world had already completed the digital transition and had done so through their governments, despite having highly specialised technical bodies at their disposal.
He stated that it is not possible for the government, by issuing a dissenting decree that to some extent encroaches on the sphere of congressional powers, to introduce into the area of administration the observance of laws prepared by the legislative branch.
In Michoacán they analyze the possibility of counting "voice by voice"
According to data published by PREP, the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is less than 27 percent. The votes of 879 out of 6,074 constituencies have not yet been counted.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" appeared in this year's elections in Michoacán, where, according to data published by the Preliminary Election Results Program (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the election of the governor is less than 27 percent, and the votes of 879 out of 6,074 constituencies have not yet been counted.
In this context, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the electoral authority approved a whole series of measures that should harmonize local norms with the federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán has not officially confirmed its political constitution, nor its State Electoral Code or the Electoral Justice Law. The State Congress passed the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force was due to expire during this term, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel neglected to publish them within the deadline in the Official State Gazette Act, saying that he had some objections to them.
On November 9, the Supreme State Court (SCJN) resolved a constitutional dispute initiated by the local legislature, declaring the head of state's vote on constitutional reforms "null and void" because he had the right to "neither approve nor veto" them.
When asked about the possibility of counting 'vote by vote', María de los Ángeles Llanderal replied that thanks to the approval of the relevant measures by the IEM General Council, it would be possible for both partial and total counts to be carried out by the local electoral authority.
In this way, a partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, can be carried out under the following conditions: the election results do not match; there is no record of the counting and calculation in the relevant box or is not available to the President; or if there were mistakes and obvious violations of the election results.
Moreover, a total recount of votes in all ballot boxes may be carried out if there is evidence that the difference between the potential winner of the election and the candidate in second place is less than or equal to one percentage point; whenever at the beginning of the session there is an explicit request from the representative of the party and/or coalition that proposed the candidate in second place.
A total recount of votes may also be carried out if, after a proper count, it is found that the difference between the likely winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, and also whenever there is an explicit request by the political party whose candidate finished second. In this case, electoral packages that have been partially counted will be discarded.
It should be noted that this is the situation in the Morelia elections, where, according to the PREP, the difference between first and second place is less than 0.16%, although 129 of the 923 constituencies have not yet been counted.
