A new Italian government will be appointed on Wednesday
Appointed Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet the Italian President tomorrow to present him with the new government that will face the crisis that is keeping the country on the brink of economic disaster.
Tomorrow, the appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet the Italian President to present him with a new government that will face the crisis that is holding the country on the brink of economic catastrophe and that has put the entire euro area at risk.
The presidential palace issued a report announcing that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he could form a government.
It is expected to present a government composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present to the president the results of his talks he held with political parties in an effort to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say that he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments suggested that the obstacles were overcome.
"The framework is now well marked," he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, a much shorter time than usual. Meanwhile, Italy is trying to combat the political and financial crisis, which has sent debt levels to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the tough austerity package demanded by European leaders. Only in this way will it be possible to restore Italy's damaged credibility.
There is a lot of pressure on Monti to hurry. Due to market volatility, interest rates on Italian BTP bonds with ten-year maturities exceeded the 7 percent mark, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to apply for bailouts.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian employers' organisation Confindustria, told reporters after her meeting with Monti: "We said we would strongly support this government."
We believe that this government is the last chance to get Italy out of this predicament.
Monti's hopes of success have been greatly multiplied thanks to support from Silvio Berlusconi's PDL, who was forced to resign by the crisis on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined for good results," Angelina Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
Support for the PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because, up to now, many of its members have opposed the government with a technocratic majority formed by Monti.
Parliamentary support
Monti's new government must have strong parliamentary support in order to push through unpopular austerity reforms.
Any obstacle or delay in the effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
Italy's Foreign Banks Association has joined the pressure, warning that Monti's failure could spell disaster.
Monti began talks with political parties, trade unions and business groups, youth and women's organizations on Monday.
The round of negotiations will conclude on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by President Napolitano, who allowed for rapid progress in response to the crisis.
After a brief decline late last week, when it was already clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian bond rates have returned to critical levels, responding to uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will be successful.
Rescuing Italy, whose public debt is €1.8 trillion, would be beyond the capabilities of the eurozone's current financial reserves.
Monti has said his government should stay in power until the next election, scheduled for 2013, despite general forecasts that politicians will only give him time to carry out reforms and then call early elections.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that the government must be composed only of experts to lead Italy out of the predicament the country has found itself in because of financial pressure.
Political sources said that mutual mistrust and disagreement between the parties was complicating the attempt to include political figures in the government.
