What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, we have no restrictions on what we can't do.
We will try to perform the best possible show with a variety of songs. We will try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat repertoire.
Why?
I think part of it is because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to choose what songs we play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven't played for a long time, we focus on them and we are also surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that we may have forgotten about it.
That's how the show is more interesting for us, and that's why I think it's more interesting for people.
With this tour you are celebrating 20 years of artistic career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you've done?
Yes, definitely.
First of all, I don't think any of us could have imagined that we would be in one big rock band and stay in it for more than 20 years. That sounds like a dream.
We realize how much we have been given and we are moved that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we like to make music.
We are lucky to be able to see the places we have always longed for.
We couldn't have done better.
What did it mean to you to be a significant part of the emergence of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group, which includes all the greats.
The people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It's surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends, it doesn't happen very often.
From time to time a group is formed in a city, but it is much less common for five or ten groups to emerge from one city at a time.
We are proud of that and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play with some of them.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are fortunate that they are all our friends, and we are honored to be a part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It's also very unusual for a group like yours to stick together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt [Cameron] joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than the usual duration of the group.
I think firstly, we are all lucky to still be in this world, and secondly, the fact that we are constantly interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends and thanks to this we have managed to open musical paths that leave everyone enough freedom to experiment on their own.
We trust each other, we appreciate each other's music and I don't think it could be better.
Your relationship with the word fame was not easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do whatever you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew, it became easier and easier to find a balance.
We try not to tour too much because it's very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for music, you remind yourself that you have to respect the music and what you gave it. You must not get carried away by being a famous, rock star. Neither of us ever really cared about that.
How do you remember another Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote great songs and in the beginning it was something spectacular.
We existed as a band for three years and never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. The most important thing is that even today we are friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at the photos, I remember Andy, how incredible he was, how I laughed with him. It was always a pleasure to work with him, laugh, talk about music or football and much more.
She was an incredible person and we miss her so much.
The Las Robertas National Band will be commissioned to open a show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that is why you chose them as opening acts?
Yes, the production sent us videos with several suggestions and we liked this group the most. That's why we're curious to see what Las Robertas will offer live and they have to be very fun.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed [Eddie Vedder], so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he adds the first thing that comes to mind.
Who influences you as a bass player?
Lots of people.
The first ones that come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all evening about the bass players I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge even though it's no longer fashionable?
I think we've all always felt slightly separated from the word grunge.
When I think of grunge, I think of the bands I mentioned as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana, and all the others that were formed at the same time. And if that's still the way music is valid today, that's great, because it's music worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are playing better music today than ever before.
In the beginning, your music had a slightly gloomy character, and now it is more positive.
What is behind this change?
That's interesting because I feel like there are a few songs in the new album that are lighter, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very gloomy, even though they may sound positive.
With both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried, and they are deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and you have some trauma in your life, you lose a family member or a friend, those things start to affect your art and your music, and these two songs represent that to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make gloomy music.
