Fujimori was hospitalized again for medical tests
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized Tuesday at a public hospital where he will be tested for muscle loss in his lower limbs, his attending physician said.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights abuses committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several illnesses, including tongue cancer, for which he underwent four surgeries and is currently under control by doctors.
MP Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal doctor, told Canal N television that Fujimori will undergo tests at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases over three days to find out why he is in pain and why he is losing strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga said that in his opinion, Fujimori could receive a pardon on humanitarian grounds, but the former president himself does not want a pardon because he feels innocent.
He was operated four times for tongue cancer, lost 18 kilograms, and these problems were compounded by other ailments such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst on the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been serving his sentence since September 2007 in the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people who were killed by a murderous squadron of troops operating illegally in the early years of his rule.
Mujica visits Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Mujica, accompanied by several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday. Its aim is to achieve an expansion of trade between the two nations and to touch on the political issues of the region.
Mujica will meet his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, on Wednesday. This is the most important meeting of an extensive visit full of meetings with representatives of politics, business and representatives of the Uruguyan community living in Mexico. The program was published by the Uruguayan Presidential Office.
The meeting of the two presidents in Guadalajara will serve to exchange information on political issues between the two countries," the Uruguayan presidential office said on its website.
According to local media, Mujica will try to get Calderón to support Uruguay in a dispute with France that occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy listed the South American country as a tax haven at a G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened that countries that continue to be tax havens will be excluded from the international community. This statement provoked a negative opinion from Uruguay and consultations with the ambassador to that European country.
Mexico has held the G20 presidency since November. The G20 is a group made up of the world's most powerful emerging and developed countries. Since January this year, it has concluded an agreement on the exchange of information with the Latin American country to prevent double taxation.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has sought to concretize fiscal exchange agreements in order to get out of the "blacklist" of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), which includes countries that have not implemented all the required international standards for tax cooperation.
From a trade point of view, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) since 2004, which has increased the exchange of goods between the two countries.
Bearded plumber runs in 3D thanks to "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has been fighting tirelessly for more than 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the villain Bowser, but he has never appeared in 3D before: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the love of a girl with stereoscopic technology.
The title, which comes to all stores around the world this month, was created from the beginning to take advantage of all the characteristics offered by the Nintendo 3DS portable console, which allows you to play three-dimensional games without having to use glasses.
"Mario is a character who has to tell how stereoscopy without glasses is supposed to work," said Omar Álvarez, a press specialist at Nintendo in Spain, during a video game presentation in Madrid.
Álvarez stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "Nintendo's first video game created specifically for this medium" because to date, successful films such as "Star Fox 64 3D" and "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
A Nintendo spokesperson said that in addition to the image being 3D, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "affordable" video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and fluid game.
Álvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" includes two games in one: the first part is "simple", whose task is to attract less skilled users.
Once you have overcome this level, you can embark on the "second round" at levels of the game, which are more challenging this time.
In addition, users can choose real-time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action. However, it will be necessary to play in 3D in order to overcome various challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
This new arrival of Super Mario in 3D also anticipates with the return of the character to the portable console, which has not happened since 2005.
In this video game, Nintendo plays to those who follow the saga and repeats the successful formula from previous parts. It consists in the fact that the plumber of the bearded man will have to go through dangerous mined platforms to free Princess Peach.
Although the player will find novelties in movements, surroundings, disguises and also among enemies, the "playful" Luigi will also appear.
Colom approves Portillo's extradition to the United States
President Alvaro Colom announced on Tuesday that he had moved forward on the extradition of former President Alfonso Portillo, who is to answer in the United States for plotting to launder $70 million.
Thus ends a process aimed at Guatemala responding to a request from a northern country demanding Portillo's extradition so that it can try him.
At the press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision is in line with the independence of the judiciary and executive and that he remembers that the criminal court has already ordered extradition.
He assured that during his mandate he "did not interfere" in court decisions and allowed all extradition that came to his desk.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín will be extradited for murder and grievous bodily harm and Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
Colom's move marks a move of execution after all judicial and constitutional instances have been exhausted to lead a trial against the former president, who ruled from 2000 to 2004.
In accordance with the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Tribunal and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo will be extradited after his legal situation in Guatemala has been resolved and respect for human rights has been guaranteed.
Portillo was found not guilty of embezzling $120 million from the Department of Defense during his presidency. This process preceded the extradition, but the Public Ministry appealed, bringing the case back into play.
Trinijove helped 6,000 young people in a state of danger
The organization was created to help children without education so that they do not find themselves on the margins of society.
The balance of the first 25 years of the existence of the Trinijove social support organization is very important: 6,000 young people at risk of social exclusion received help. The organization has been helping them overcome difficult situations for 25 years.
To this must be added the long hundreds of jobs that have been created for this social group.
Yesterday's anniversary also served to present the balance sheet at a ceremony that took place in the former Fabra i Coats factory and was attended by more than 300 people.
Trinijove was founded in Trinitat Vella in 1986 to help young people with little education, no job, drug addiction or social exclusion.
Yesterday's meeting in Sant Andrea was attended by a large number of representatives of organizations and institutions that have cooperated with the association over the past 25 years.
The diverse political representation, at the time of the elections, showed the unified character of the work carried out by the Trinijos.
Together with the President of the Generalitat, Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the ceremony was attended by former Socialist adviser on education, Ernest Maragall, and former Deputy Mayor and current Ecological-Socialist Councillor Ricard Goma.
The grand hall of Fabra i Coats was also attended by the current advisor for social welfare and family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the general director of social work at La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas said that Trinijove was created in a very difficult time and that today's times also present a number of obstacles, but added that the work that the association has brought to date "is a good foundation".
The president cited Trinijove as an example of how it is possible to combat adverse circumstances and how to give courage to people in difficult situations.
"The crisis is nothing new for this organization and for the work it does," he said.
A seized house was evicted, where gigantic parties were held
The intruders appropriated 11 of the 13 apartments in the Balmes building, 51
The 12 occupiers left the house at noon yesterday without resistance
Everything indicates that the nightmare experienced by the neighbours of number 51 in Balmes Street is finally over.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building they were illegally occupying at noon yesterday, where they organized gigantic parties to wake up neighbors. They left the building by order of the court and without the police having to intervene.
After the end of the operation, the lock on the door was replaced to prevent a recurrence of the situation.
"From now on, the entrance will be guarded," the caretaker said.
The occupiers who occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building - the rest are inhabited - took away all the electrical and partly also the water equipment, in addition to painting the walls and leaving behind garbage of all kinds, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
In the first three apartments, huge parties were held, which lasted up to two days and woke up the other tenants.
Next to the building is a disco, Balmes 51, which was also damaged.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, explained to Europa Press that sales fell by 80% while the building was occupied.
The owner of the disco points out that the occupiers of the building made her unfair competition because they sold drinks for 3 euros, while the disco costs 10.
In addition, the owner of an entertainment venue had to respond to lawsuits from neighbors over noise. But the problems were not caused by visitors to the disco, but by the residents of the occupied house and especially by those who attended the parties organized here, whose frequency and intensity has increased in recent weeks, according to the angry residents of the neighborhood.
The owner of the disco explained that the problems were so great that they even agreed with the owner of the building and have been forgiving her rent for nine months.
The city police also confirmed that they have received more complaints from neighbors about the situation in recent weeks.
Last week, Alberto Fernández Díaz, chairman of the PP People's Group, demanded that "the building be immediately evicted to put an end to the problems of civil coexistence suffered by neighbours and the destruction of the area".
The leader of the People's Party explained that only one floor was occupied before the summer, but in recent months the occupiers have entered all floors of the building and almost all the apartments, and in one of them there have even been thefts.
In this regard, he added that "impunity must be ended and consistent with the acts against civic responsibility that took place in the building."
Yesterday, the city police also cleared the building in Nou Barris.
At 3:30 p.m., police entered Building 35 on Mont-ral Street after being called by neighbors who saw four people entering the building.
All four were immediately detained.
Park or mountains?
The architects met on the occasion of the announcement of the proceedings, which entails more than a controversy over fees
The city's tender for 16 gates reopens the debate on the role of the Collserola Park in Barcelona.
In the mid-80s, in the heyday of the defunct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), the municipality printed several pamphlets in support of the Collserola Park.
The leaflet defined the mountain as a large park of metropolitan Barcelona.
What's more, it was supplemented by a numerical comparison with New York's Central Park.
After the demise of CMB in 1987, the park returned to the minds of many as the upper frontier of Barcelona. The Catalan metropolis is one of the few that do not orient themselves on the north-south axis, but up (mountain) - down (sea).
Collserola's qualification as a nature park goes in this direction.
The reference was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild boars instead of Yogi bear.
This was the position until September, when the town hall announced a mega competition consisting of 16 competitions for the same number of entrance gates to Collserola.
Of course, the gate is more in favour of the idea of a park.
Either this, or someone is trying to place a gate on the field.
The only question is: Collserola, park or mountain?
During the competition, both from a purely organizational point of view and on the basis of reflections on the city, this question becomes a central theme of all Barcelona architects.
It's already as trite a topic as when two members of this old caste of the chosen ones shake hands when meeting in an elevator.
And it was this undertaking that sparked one of the rare coincidences between what three Barcelona architects and the outgoing university professors think.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: the selection process is justified.
According to Roldán, after the question of the bay side was raised, "the mountain side should also be discussed", so Ildefons Cerdo's speech on green apples was not carried through.
"We have to start from the principle that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, its great accessibility.
Collserola is more complex", declared the architect, for whom the name "gateways to Collserol" implies a "lexicological trap": we must not imagine them "as entrances to a park, but rather as defining zones where it is possible to operate".
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in the world of urbanism, describes the design as an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
The danger arising from the "uncertainty represented today by the project of a public place" after the experience of the 80s, which had "its swan song" in the Forum area.
The first concern is the very demarcation of the boundaries where it should be built.
"To define something is to take the next step", that is, in principle, to move one step further.
"It is necessary to keep in mind the new urban planning and planning tools, because the current ones (with reference to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM)) can cause a real disaster."
Looking at the question in more detail, Modol believes that the Collserola valley slope can be "considered a park", but the Barcelona part cannot, for purely topographical reasons.
Modol also recalled that there is already work done by the Patronat de Collserola that "must not end up in the rubbish heap", although he welcomes the fact that the town hall offers his committee to intervene in the project from the "first moment".
Moreover, he understands that the proximity of the mountain to the city is a kind of pass that allows architects to engage in debate, but he "doubts" that it should be this technical profile that will lead the multidisciplinary teams ("it's all about skill," he adds) that need to be created: "Architects should only be tools".
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question that gave the name to this game is complex, because Collserolo's global vision is missing from the tender documents: "16 tenders have been announced that deal with all the axis of the mountain - the sea, but there is no longitudinal study that would look at the area and understand it as a whole."
This means that at least he applied for all 16 tenders.
Otherwise, the project of one gate may clash with the concept and definition of the architect of the neighboring gate.
In his opinion, the city hall should guarantee that the strip located immediately above the Ronda de Dalt should provide a full-length amenities zone that would ensure a smooth transition between the city and the greenery.
Casino pardons Jonas Larrazábal, who will be fired
After 72 days of imprisonment, Cadino Red's legal commissioner granted a pardon to the brother of the mayor of Monterrey in a trial in which he was prosecuted for alleged extortion.
Manuel Jonás Larrazábal spent 72 days in prison and will now be released after Casino Red's legal representative granted him a pardon before the Second Criminal Court in the district, which heard the extortion case in which the brother of the mayor of Monterrey was indicted.
After the Casino Royale bombing, the owner of Casino Red, Sergio Gil García, published a series of photos and videos in which Manuel Jonás allegedly demanded that he pay an economic quota so that the Monterrey City Hall would allow an illegal operation in the betting house.
After a public indictment, the State Prosecutor's Office opened a criminal case against the brother of the Panist Mayor. On September 2, he was detained and imprisoned for 30 days.
Then, after 4 hours spent in front of the Public Ministry Agent No. 3 for property crimes, he was transferred to Prison 1, located in Barrio Antiguo in the capital of the state.
He remained in this place for the next 49 days after the second detention order was issued and a Public Ministry agent refuted the possibility of complicity or organized crime.
On October 19, he was taken to the criminal court in Cadereyta on suspicion of blackmailing the owners of Casino Red with the sum of one and a half million pesos. However, he remained in a medium-supervised prison for only a few hours because he received death threats.
Leaders allowed him to remain in city cells in San Nicolás de los Garza during the trial.
On October 25, he was presented with an arrest warrant issued by the Secretary of the Second Criminal Court, Jorge Yánez, who said that after almost two months of investigation, enough evidence had been gathered to prove Jonah's guilt. The evidence includes, for example, the payment of 1.5 million pesos to casino representatives in exchange for a promise that the operation will be allowed.
On Monday, Casino Red's legal representative, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, appeared before Judge José Luis Pecina and asked for a pardon for the brother of the region's mayor. Based on this, he will soon be able to return to freedom.
During the legal hearing, the representative of the Public Ministry assigned to the court, Ramiro Arias, asked García Gómez if the damage had been repaired and which of the companions had decided to grant a pardon. But the lawyer made it clear that the name would remain secret.
On the basis of official file 197/2011, a legal pardon is granted to Jonas Larrazábal. It will not be possible to file any complaint in the proceedings against him. It is also not possible to claim compensation for damages or punishment.
After a hearing with a legal representative around 3:50 p.m., the court ordered the immediate release of Larrazábal Bretón.
The registrar of the court, Jorge Yanéz, went to the prison in San Nicolás de los Garza to tell Jonas that he had been granted an official pardon and that his case had been placed in the archives.
He also told him that the judge had issued an immediate order for his release.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome presented details of the plane crash that killed the governor's secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven other people.
The Secretariat of Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the investigation into the accident that killed Cabinet Secretary Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people showed that the helicopter landed directly on the terrain with full force, without the pilot having a chance to attempt a forced landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, secretary for communications and transport, said that before the plane took off, the pilot stated that the weather conditions allowed the flight.
"Parts that appear indicate that the unit came into contact with the terrain several times, the wings entangled in the branches of trees 25 meters from where the unit lost the hull."
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it met all the requirements for transporting personnel.
In addition, he stated that as a result of an investigation conducted in the area of impact, no parts were found on the ground.
"During the search, it was found that the parts of the aircraft were not located in another location, so the aircraft hit the mainland as a whole.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 people, it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The terrain shows a slope with a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The Secretary assured that at the moment the most important thing is to get results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation may take several months or up to a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, director general of airports and auxiliary services, said that at the moment of impact, the Presidential General Staff helicopter was moving at cruise speed and the accident occurred on soft ascending terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that it was a normal overflight operation at the time of the accident," he said.
At a press conference, SCT representative Pérez Jácome listed six main points of the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, that is, the crew must see the terrain during the flight.
Meteorological conditions:
Reports in AICM indicate adequate conditions during takeoff, accordingly the aircraft is advancing towards the border, between DF and the State of Mexico were visible cloud layers at low altitudes.
Routes selected:
It is likely that because of the clouds, the crew was looking for a lower area and greater visibility up to the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last radar record of the helicopter match, it is likely that there was no loss of control or disruption of the flight trajectory before the impact.
Distribution of aircraft remains in a limited area:
The information we currently have allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a straight trajectory and from the side.
A diagram of the dispersion of the remnants of the aircraft indicates that the helicopter was whole at the time of impact on land.
No fire or explosion was reported.
No evidence was recorded at the crash site to suggest that an explosion or fire had occurred.
The latest results of the investigation show that there may have been several contacts with the mainland.
During the fieldwork, the remains of the aircraft were found at an altitude of up to 9200 feet above sea level, the terrain slopes, the height of the slope goes from seven to 30 degrees.
The photographs show footage in which there was probably a breakup along the mentioned route.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have come into contact with the ground in several places.
After careful searching in the vicinity of the accident, in an area that is larger than the area of demarcation, the remains of the helicopter were not found, which reinforces the assumption that the impact occurred in a state when the helicopter was still whole.
Mexico's Health Insurance Institute has begun research into the gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research to discover the gene responsible for obesity in children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the IPN Institute
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to uncover a gene that causes obesity in children and youth. The research, entitled "Genetics of obesity in children and adolescents", will allow to obtain results regarding overweight.
In the report, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Specialized Hospital of the National Medical Center of the 21st Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team composed of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers has been established.
This team relies on the support of specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public, whether or not authorized, can also participate in the research. People can come to the participating IMSS sports centers in Mexico City, where teenage tests will be performed every day from 8 a.m.
He pointed out that the research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Center (Mexican State) and since October 8, this activity has also been carried out at the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Center (East of the Mexican State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children are obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to determine the components and importance of genetics when it comes to the development of obesity, and to trace risk factors in Mexican children and young people, thereby preventing the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of International Diabetes Day, celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim is to collect data from three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on nutrition.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He specified that every Saturday anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference) are performed on all participants, blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglicerides, cholesterol, insulin levels are determined and genes are examined (genes are tried to identify genes that are involved in childhood obesity).
Cruz López said the research reflects health professionals' concern about the alarming increase in children's weight.
'Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, there was a 77% increase in obesity for boys alone and 47% for girls. There has also been a dramatic increase in the case of overweight', the IMSS expert said.
He said that one of the reasons for looking for indicators is the assumption that the population of a country differs from other populations by its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic makeup, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in the genes that are responsible for the development of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that, in general, the genetics of obesity are commonly explained as the inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and that is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they receive an overall assessment of the children's condition, thereby determining whether they show any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearms indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-diabetes conditions.
The information is still confidential, doctors pass it on in writing to parents and explain all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make to avoid their children's disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main ingredients that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle meaning a lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the TV all day, and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
Overweight is also caused by a large caloric intake, that is, greater consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins, and genetic load, which is the subject of this research.
There will be no potholes in the asphalt from UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, creates modified asphalts with polymers to create a mixture that has better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature
If the pavement was properly cared for, there would be no need to repair almost 200,000 potholes after each rainy season in the Valle de Mexico Metropolitan Area, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM, who added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt paving were adequate, potholes would be significantly reduced or even eliminated altogether.
In his lecture The Technological Cause of Potholes, which he gave as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalts with polymers, which should create a mixture that has similar characteristics to asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believes that this kind of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country. This would improve functionality and reduce pothole formation.
He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of oil, is a collection of hydrocarbon molecules, high molecular weight molecules called asphaltenes, and others with low molecular weight, which are called mortenes. Together, they give asphalt its typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a fluid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost solid, while at low temperatures the asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but varies during the day according to meteorological conditions and temperature, the chemical engineering expert pointed out.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most streets in Mexico City are covered with flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Between the uppermost layers there is an asphalt liner, formed by small pebbles embedded in the asphalt and then compressed.
He emphasized that every stone that makes up the insert is covered with asphalt.
When cars pass or when creating pressure, it is possible for the forces in the pavement to be well distributed.
If it were modified asphalt, they would decompose even better, the chemical engineer believes.
He added that the last layer, called the shell, will be placed on the asphalt liner, made up of fine stones, i.e. sand also embedded in the asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with the rims of vehicles, it must have greater mechanical force than asphalt liner and must ensure road friction.
Due to the fact that as part of the paving it will be subjected to heavy loads, the cladding must be of sufficient thickness and care must be taken of the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. Water in particular has a great influence on the functionality of the asphalt liner.
Once the terrain is wet, the water spreads inwards and it is difficult for it to get out, causing all layers of pavement to soften and thus create potholes.
He explained that during the formation of potholes, the film of the shell is first damaged, and only then the asphalt liner is damaged. However, damage does not happen in a single moment, but is a gradual process that should be stopped at the first signs with appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that vehicle loads are another important factor in potholes, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of pavement must match the load on the vehicles and ensure that this load is not exceeded. This is the only way to prevent frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there is still a lot of work to be done on asphalt and the research is at the beginning. It is worth mentioning, for example, bituminous emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and allow us to easily repair potholes without having to use high temperatures.
