Such was the work of a resident of Cali who identified the corpse of Alfonso Can
A fingerprint expert from Cali has gone down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4 last year, a fingerprint expert from CTI in Cali made history as the man who confirmed the identity of the Supreme Leader of the Farc: "Alfons Cano", through a fingerprint comparison.
Of the seven fingerprint experts working in the CTI department, it was the turn of Eliazar González, a Puerto Tejada man who has worked in forensic research for 21 years.
Early in his career, González worked at the town hall in Chocó, where he often had to rummage through the forest for more than five days to get to the place where the corpses were that needed to be identified.
In 2000, he moved to the capital Valle and, after completing the relevant courses, began to specialize in fingerprints. This science deals with the study of friction of the skin, that is, the palms of the hands and feet.
During the week of the operation against said Alphonse Cano, Eliazar was told to take his clothes with him for at least three days.
Something big was expected.
On Friday night he set off for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmiro.
He knew that he would have to identify two corpses and that he suspected that one of them was the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world. He was asked to take a fingerprint card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigation team at the place where the corpse was located, he did not recognize it because of its physical appearance. He looked completely different from what he did in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a villager in the area, without glasses, much slimmer.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Along with a galton magnifying glass, ink and a transplanter, and a light, Eliazar began to compare the dactyl records of the corpse with those from the card.
The eye did not disappoint him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the Puerto Tejado-born man was instructed to confirm to Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinzón whether he was indeed the commander-in-chief of the Farc.
Search for clues
For the dactyloscope from Sijín de Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos gave to Eliazar González at the press conference of the operational service against "Cano" is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, without the possibility of error, which can play a key role in deciding crimes.
In addition to identifying the corpses, these people help in research into crimes such as theft or murder and confirm the identities of those caught.
When they are caught, many offenders present false documents or have no papers at all.
We take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The investigator said that in case of injury, he had to remove a piece of the wall of the house in the house, because in this place the thief leaned to pull out a safe full of jewelry and money.
The walls are difficult because they are not intended for fingerprinting, but in this case we were able to obtain a full handprint and identify the perpetrator who was involved in several thefts," he said.
Fingerprints can also confirm or refute suspicions in a murder case.
Not long ago, they found a dead man with bottles of alcohol around him.
As a result of the investigation, it was determined that one of the family members could be responsible for the murder and the imprint on the bottle confirmed this.
Although it cannot be confirmed for sure that he was indeed a murderer, it is clear that he appeared on the scene of a crime.
A fingerprint expert from CTI explained that the fingerprints of objects are "wiped off using chemical or physical reactive substances."
When they appear, a transplant or tape is used to collect them.
The fingerprints are then sent to Asif, which is a database of offenders, or to the Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians at the moment whose data is not recorded anywhere," the CTI expert said.
He explained that not everything is as it appears in the CSI television program.
Just as everything that glitters is not gold, not everything you touch leaves traces.
However, if it can be used, an appropriate comparison must be made.
