Austria
Writing the Golden Balance Rule into the Constitution
The government of the grand coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to write a "golden rule" of budgetary policy into the constitution in order to reduce the public deficit and avoid a possible downgrade of Austria's rating by rating agencies (AAA).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor himself, Werner Faymann, who announced this decision at the end of the ministerial meeting, in a situation where Austria's public debt, at 74.6%, is well above the criterion of a maximum of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty, but much lower than that of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency were reduced by just one notch from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros more in interest every year," argued Vice Chancellor and Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger, a Democrat of the Wings.
Austria thus follows the request of the Eurozone summit held in Brussels on 26 October 2011, where the Heads of State and Government strongly requested that by the end of 2012 the reduction of the public deficit and the achievement of a balance in the public accounts be written into a constitution or law of the same value.
The instrument adopted by the Austrian government is close to the "German model", Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the public structural deficit will have to fall by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) every year, and from 2017 onwards, the federal state's public structural deficit will not be allowed to exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while the Länder as well as municipalities will have to report a balanced budget.
The aim is to bring public debt below the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/21.
