Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogma
If there is one issue that cannot be grasped on short-term balance sheets or under emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and price of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of enterprises.
It is natural that the meeting at the elections should be an opportunity to think about such deposits and the place occupied by the energy from the core.
The debate will only be successful if all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options are examined.
The French must base their position on objective facts and rational data.
So far, there are 7 billion human beings on the planet, but demographic developments will cause a doubling of electricity demand between now and 2050, unless we want to deprive a significant part of the world's population of an important part of life.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources will have to be tackled in order to continue generating electricity, not forgetting the imperative need to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases in order to combat climate change, a topic that is currently disappearing from environmental debates.
The Fukushima accident does not affect any of these parameters.
That is why Germany stands alone in its decision to reject nuclear power.
However, this is not the case for Belgium, which is making its decision conditional on the need to find some other source capable of replacing itself, nor Switzerland, which considers it right to build only the latest generation of power stations.
On the contrary, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to quote at least some countries, are continuing with their projects with determination.
After Fukushima, the United States decided to expand its fleet by one unit by resuming construction of one plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model based on renewable energies is sometimes presented as an example, reality contradicts this.
The choice of Berlin will be reflected in the price of electricity, increased energy dependence on gas imported especially from Russia, a sharp increase in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of natural gas and coal power plants.
We will feel all these unpleasant effects within a few months.
The case of Denmark deserves to be considered.
The European wind power champion, from which it gets 30% of its electricity, is also one of the largest consumers of coal and gas due to wind irregularities, which has made CO2 emissions and Danish electricity prices 65% and 50% higher than the European average, respectively.
On the contrary, thanks to the immutability of our energy policy, our neighbours will pay electricity bills 40% more than those paid by French households.
While in a globalised economy energy costs are a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of keeping industry on national territory, French companies enjoy the advantages of the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear energy would trigger a strong increase in the price of electricity, which would make illusory beautiful statements about the reindustrialisation of our country and the defence of purchasing power.
A price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay, just as they are fundamentally opposed to this energy, as opinion polls show.
Let us recall that the energy policy of our country has made it possible to build an industry with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 related jobs.
A strong exporting sector is dragging a large number of SMEs to international markets, creating jobs that cannot be offshored.
If France decided to abandon nuclear power, it would sacrifice a considerable number of these small and medium-sized enterprises and lose the €6 billion a year that the country receives for exporting nuclear equipment and services.
What plant owner would order a nuclear reactor designed to run for 60 years while its manufacturer was scheduled to go bankrupt?
In solving the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no magic source for energy production, or even a diabolical one.
The development of low-CO2 installations, nuclear installations and installations using renewable energy sources by the French industrial group AREVA shows the complementarity of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute necessity.
In France, we have the National Office for Nuclear Safety, which carries out uncompromising and transparent supervision of existing nuclear power stations, as well as of the construction of the new power station in Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, have the idea of safety in their blood.
In fifty years, the nuclear industry has known three serious accidents.
The only one in Three Mile Island took place under normal traffic conditions and remained without human casualties or consequences for the environment.
At Chernobyl, the drama was caused by reactor designs and inexcusable human error.
In the case of Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural disasters on an unprecedented scale, which caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn the lessons of this accident as it did from the previous two.
The fruit of this move and of the cooperation between the French and German nuclear safety authorities, operators and designers is that the EPR reactor is a concept capable of withstanding such phenomena.
While it is respected by all those wishing to build a nuclear power plant, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be an excellent gift offered to competitors of the AREVA Group and EDF and clearing the way for them to seize a leading position in nuclear development.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best energy solutions for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and machinations dominate a debate so decisive for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy implemented under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticised from various angles - the overloading of the police, courts and administration subjected to a policy of numbers, the compatibility of this policy with the 'country of human rights' status that France boasts of.
More recently, it was the administrative harassment of foreign students that became topical when the interior minister (see Libération of May 23) declared that France "does not need foreign talent, bricklayers and waitresses."
But until now, it has rarely been discussed from the point of view of economics.
It has to be said that there is a fairly broad consensus between left and right in this area.
Jacques Chirac set the tone on the right in 1976 when he declared that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with 2 million immigrant workers," and on the left, Michel Rocard said in 1990 that France "cannot accept all the misery of the world."
The only difference is the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of an invasion of French territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on both the right and the left.
In both camps, immigrants are seen as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference lies in the degree of generosity we deign to give immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande confines himself to banalities when he states that joint development will make it possible to solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden and problem may be true in elections, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in their recent work synthesizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.): there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration movements on economic growth, wages and employment in countries.  which accept immigrants.
Restricting immigration cripples growth and hurts employment.
Concerns about the impact caused by migrants are based on the idea that these people can replace French workers, especially the less skilled, and put pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more of a complement than substitutes for French employees by performing jobs in sectors with underemployed staff.
Low-skilled immigrants in sectors that do not attract French workers, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where education is not enough to offer jobs.
Positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, these additions between the French and migrants cause the arrival of immigrants to have a positive effect on the wages and employment of French workers.
Giovanni Peri thus calculated that a 1% increase in migration movements would cause a long-term increase in real wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And it ignores the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to thought-building and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, PayPal, eBay, and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors of social systems in European countries, amounting to an average of 1% of the total budget.
For example, the World Labour Organization estimates that in Germany one migrant arriving at the age of 30 will bring a net contribution (income minus expenses) of €150,000 to public budgets over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy expressed at the beginning of his mandate the wish to go "bared teeth" for the missing percentage of growth.
These teeth used to deter immigrants had the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, European democracy remains to be thought through
Democracy is a rare and very fragile commodity.
The European continent should remember this, because despite having invented it in Athens two thousand years ago, it experienced the tragedies of world wars, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, gulags, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and colonels in Greece during the XX century.
Some people may have believed that in order for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be enough to make a choice and carry it out in the most direct way possible.
However, it is known from Napoleon that it was an ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, while a necessary condition for democracy, is not a sufficient condition and can become an "instrument of oppression," as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: public space, public spirit, values, organization of departments and control of power, education, enlightenment, social and economic solidarity, justice.
The crisis of Europe that we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is just as and from the beginning a crisis of politics and democracy.
Admitting the mistake of the Greek yes-no referendum will be worth a double revelation in this respect: revealing the need for a major return to political power, but also revealing a disturbing sense of its impossibility, of its impropriety.
This ambivalence must be thought through in order to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the Democratic race have now shifted, and that many of the Republican fighters are no longer firing in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain by demanding a series of national referendums organised on a necessari-by-necessity basis and in a disorganised manner.
A blank exposed to a European absolute monarch or a leap with your feet tied into the emptiness of nationalist depths: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want guillotine knives, but a common, full-fledged, peaceful and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - indeed, we would not even know where to stop the list - because the crisis is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe, bowing to the dictates of the markets and rating agencies, that suffers from its incompetence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing its sovereignty and with it each of its peoples.
There is an urgent need to restore governance of the European project of democratic sovereignty.
For only together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of their debts, rid themselves of the rule of the markets, and prepare the future by investing.
Exit from the crisis will presuppose decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, otherwise it would lead us to disaster.
After fighting for a long time against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone today is strongly calling for a European economic government.
So.
But to think so without stronger political and democratic integration, and experienced as such by citizens, would be a new folly and a new dead end.
We must take on a new stage in European construction.
In order to create a republic in France, it was necessary to "be" republicans.
A revolution in interests could not be enough.
That lesson remains valid.
We need to build a Europe that is more economically integrated.
