"Contactless" smart cards are spreading
In an optimistic atmosphere, the World Smart Card Fair will open on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris.
According to the Eurosmart Cabinet, 2011 should end with an increase in world sales of microprocessor cards (bank cards, phones with SIM cards) by 11% to more than 6 billion units.
The most important segment is contactless technology, which allows you to pay on public transport or make purchases just by bringing the card close to the reader.
This year, 460 million smart cards should be sold worldwide, compared to 320 million sold a year earlier!
Their share is expected to increase further in 2012 (expected 580 million units) and reach approximately 10% of the total smart card market (6.925 million cards).
After long being dragged by the APEC countries, Europe is gaining ground in contactless payments.
Approximately 26 million Visa bank cards are already equipped with this feature and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are more modest: 400,000 contactless Visa cards have been issued.
But large chain stores work for two.
Carrefour issued 2.5 million contactless Pass MasterCards this year.
In order to move into a higher gear, banks need to equip their clients with them from now on.
"Two large French companies have committed to systematically distributing contactless bank cards to their customers in the future," announces Gérard Nébouy, CEO of Visa Europe France.
Banks are testing mobile payments
But this is only the first stage to the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
Today, only a small number of devices are equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology, which is required for transactions.
"They are late."
"But their real expansion should happen next year."
"For 2012, we estimate global sales of 80 to 120 million units," explains Marc Bertin, President of Eurosmart.
