Paris seems to have similar analyses.
An investigation into the abduction of two French men in Niger in January 2010 could help illuminate connecting bridges.
After being kidnapped by AQMI members from a restaurant in Niamey, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory were to be killed the next day at the same time as several of their captors in an operation carried out by French special forces.
In the rubble after the raid, French and Nigerian investigators were supposed to find several phones with chips belonging to terrorists.
Terrorist axis
Analysis of the calls made leads to several people in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), investigators are particularly interested in two figures: one leads to a Nigerian who has been staying for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria that is the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man said to be close to AQMI and the sect.
"This is progress, but we must undoubtedly wait for more convincing evidence before talking about operational cooperation between AQMI and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible."
