Fast success
The Boko Haram sect was founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, school and fundamentalist Mohammed Yusuf. Boko Haram, which means "Western education is a sin" in the Haoussa language, endorses the establishment of an Islamic emirate in Nigeria's Muslim north.
In this poor region, such a combination has a quick success.
The sect is politicizing itself and demanding strict adherence to Islamic Sharia law, while its adherents are launching a fight against the central government.
These people focus first on churches, bars and offices.
In 2009, Boko Haram supporters become extremely active, multiplying their attacks against police stations.
