The army surrounds the city, resulting in 800 deaths.
The sect's founder, Mohammed Yusuf, is caught and killed in prison.
From that moment on, the group became radicalized and left its place of work in the north.
At Christmas 2010, he carries out an assassination in the city of Jos, in which 80 people die, then another in the capital, Abuja.
In June, it is again in Abuja that Boko Haram attacks the police headquarters in its first suicide attack.
And in August, the local UN office will be the first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which should lead from Mauritania through Nigeria to Somalia, now worries all security specialists.
Now that al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb has encircled Mali and the iger and Somalis of the Al-Shabaab movement are operating in Kenya, Boko Haram is emerging as a new threat to the continent.
Last week in Nigeria, in a conversation with President Goodluck Jonathan Jonathan Juppé, Alain Juppé said that France was on alert and ready to "pass on all information".
