Nord Stream, a new port of Russian gas entry to Europe
The Nord Stream long-distance gas pipeline, connecting directly Eastern Europe to Russia and running along the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has become operational.
It must supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event properly.
More than 500 guests, including 4 heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that will connect Russia and Germany directly under the sea, last Tuesday.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte jointly turned the control wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic meters of Russian gas will flow to Western Europe every year through the first 1,224 km pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the state of Mecklemburg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline, which must be completed by the end of 2012, will deliver a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, an amount equivalent to the entire French consumption.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline of the gas pipeline on the same route is already being mentioned.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction has the character of a victory.
The project was strongly opposed by Poland and the Baltic countries.
In fact, Nord Stream will make it possible to supply gas directly to Germany without it being routed overland by any third country (Poland or Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries are losing some power: the possibility of pressuring Russia by threatening to cut off its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
This was expressed most strongly by Warsaw when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
That is to say that the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater certainty of its purchases.
But this is at the cost of weakening the energy Europe, because the project has created rifts between Europeans from the East and the West.
Barely 5 years ago, Russia managed to push through its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and wealthy, gas-consuming Western states whose deposits are nearing their end.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us," François Fillon confirmed at the pipeline's opening ceremony, demonstrating at what point big gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom leaders present in large numbers at Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an important technical achievement.
The subsea pipeline is made of steel with a concrete shell to protect it from anchors of naval vessels.
It rests on the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the time of the 2nd World War.
"For safety, almost a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed," says Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing like 242 Eiffel Towers, which is never interrupted by valves or maintenance stations along its entire length.
One control platform was supposed to be built near Sweden, but was rejected by project managers when the Swedes were less eager to see a Russian state-owned company permanently settling on their coast.
"In the event of a fault, we can stop the gas in less than 1 minute," explains Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline will escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builders, since the welds were designed so that a leak occurs once every 100,000 years.
The condition of the pipeline is checked from the outside by an underwater robot towed by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline is checked by a device circulating inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is pushed by gas.
At the destination, after three days of travel at a speed of 3 m/s, it will provide accurate information about possible deformation of metal parts.
The long-distance pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without the need for the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is simply provided by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom remains the leader, holding a 51% stake.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, charged with the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is headquartered in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased to the company all its gas capacity for a five-year contract, which can be renewed.
"Gazprom will profit from the total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the pipeline was provided by 30% shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach €7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, the investment costs thus rose to EUR 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will be recouped, because only Gazprom is taking the risk.
The pipeline exits the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
Valves 4.5 meters high form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of incoming gas before it is transported to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine - branded notebook
The Italian company Moleskine, founded fifty years ago, wants to once again provide the joy of writing.
It brings the smell of adventure, hours spent writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable by its black rectangular plates and its leaves of faded white color as if they had aged over time.
After all, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born in 1997.
At that time, the Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided to launch a new design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant working for the company, takes on the launch of a new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique "moleskin" (imitation leather), which is used, for example, to treat the surface of benches.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine brought back popularity to an old and forgotten object that was an icon of avant-garde artists until the XXth century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand's leader at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, settling at 12.7 million units last year.
The situation is far from the secret production of the early years, when only 3,000 notebooks were made.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries from France to the United States.
It is difficult to assemble any artificial portrait of the buyer, since the notebook will interest the businessman as well as the student or professionals.
Part of the image of the Moleskine notebook is that its owners are cosmopolitan, cultivated and open spirit.
The small Italian company, which in its beginnings had 12 employees, now has almost a hundred and since 2008 has two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
He sends his notebooks to bookstores and, through the FNAC chain of stores, to small boutiques in the city centers, where he has been able to assert his identity.
"We followed the zeitgeist and this need for new writing, despite the tumultuous development of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of the Moleskine notebook: recently the brand opened the exhibition "Treat", where architects or artists exhibit their notebook.
In August, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival, she also released new notebook plates resembling a leopard.
Moleskine benefits from its success and this cultural aura and diversifies its products: bags, diaries, pencils, laptop cases ... The brand is expanding to a wide range of carriers.
A success that aroused envy: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was bought by investment funds SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is there such a high proportion of unemployed disabled workers?
Around 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
Today opens 15. A week for employing handicapped people.
Despite the voluntarist public policies introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed disabled people is still twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% compared to 9% for the population as a whole.
Is it daunting?
"No," emphasizes Éric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, which organises Week for the Employment of the Disabled."
"The progress made in 15 years is remarkable."
"At that time, the percentage of unemployed was not two, but three times higher."
"However, much remains to be done."
It should be noted that numerous obstacles remain for unemployed disabled people before they start work.
These are the elderly: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have low qualifications: 80% do not have a high school diploma, and of the 2.3 million university students, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to work and that are 'at the heart of the problem', according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 to help businesses hire disabled workers.
So much for objective brakes.
What remains is unsaid, ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité found that managers surveyed had a "poor level of knowledge about people with disabilities" with an exaggerated image of wheelchair users and psychological or mental deficiencies.
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still a long way from reaching the target of employing 6% of disabled workers set out in the 1987 Act.
The latest known figures, from 2008, give a figure equal to 2.6%.
"We are now hovering around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organisation charged with collecting fees from businesses that do not comply with the law.
This is evidenced by the number of "fined" companies as well as the amounts paid, which fell from 59,000 offending companies to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros) between 2007 and 2011.
"The 2005 law that increased contributions created strong pressure on businesses," Pierre Blanc explains.
"But this improvement also demonstrates real awareness, especially in large enterprises."
According to the Ministry of Labor, only 59% of businesses with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of businesses with 100 to 199 employees.
